{"_id":"L9TBxzXSYHxWNEDX","name":"False Kidnapping","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">False Kidnapping</h1>\n<p>Servants of Senator Racen approach the heroes while they are in town and hand them an invitation to dine with the senator that very evening. The servants become quite insistent if the group refuses, saying their master has a most pressing matter he wishes to discuss with them.</p>\n<p>Racen greets his guests cordially and shows them into the dining room where a feast has been laid on. Once the servants have left the room Racen gets straight to business.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“My daughter, Rana, is something of a feisty child and has often spoken ill of the Emperor in public. Captain Livis, the new garrison commander, overheard her latest outburst and threatened to send her in chains to Kiera unless she married him. Of course she refused, but I had no choice but to protect her from Jant’s sadism, so I consented to the marriage.</p>\n<p>I tried to convince Livis to change his mind once he had cooled down but he refused. I admit my actions were foolish, but I cannot let my daughter marry him. I want you to kidnap my daughter from Livis’ quarters and take her to one of the Free Towns. Nowhere in Kiera will be safe for her after tonight. I have a small chest containing 8,000 pieces of eight for her to start a new life.</p>\n<p>“She must believe the kidnapping is real— tell her nothing of the truth until she is well away from here. In return I offer you a family heirloom.”</p>\n</section>\n<p>Racen pulls a rapier down from its wall mounting and hands it to the characters. The sword is called Mage Slayer and bypasses all forms of magical protection, including armor, barrier, and deflection spells.</p>\n<p>Livis’ quarters are adjacent to, but outside, the fort. Livis is spending the night in the fort but has posted 10 men to guard his rebellious bride, who is locked in the master bedroom. Any excessive noise during the rescue—such as gunshots, screams, or shouting—results in the alarm being raised. Captain Livis and twenty of his men come to investigate in 1d6+1 rounds. Livis executes any captured kidnappers out of hand.</p>\n<p>Rana is not privy to her father’s plan and believes the characters are pirates who intend to ravage and murder her. She does not listen to any attempt to explain the situation and tries to defend herself at every opportunity.</p>\n<p> Captain Livis (184): Wild Card Veteran City Watch.</p>\n<p> Soldiers (184): 10 City Watch.</p>\n<p>Rana Racen</p>\n<p>Rana is well-bred, well-educated, and extremely attractive—and she knows it. As easily as her looks turn heads her anti-Jant rhetoric causes stout Kierans to flinch. She has a rebellious streak a mile wide and a hatred of Jant that knows no limits. Attributes: Agility d6, Smarts d8, Spirit d10, Strength d6, Vigor d6 Skills: Fighting d6, Persuasion d10, Notice d6, Shooting d6, Streetwise d8, Taunt d8 Charisma: +6; Pace: 6; Parry: 5; Toughness: 5 Hindrances: Arrogant, Stubborn, Vengeful (minor) Edges: Charismatic, Strong Willed, Very Attractive Gear: Posh clothes.</p>\n<h3>Voyage from Hell</h3>\n<p>Rescuing Rana from Livis is only stage one of the kidnapping—the heroes must now take her to the safety of a Free Town. Convincing her the kidnappers are not pirates is difficult and requires a raise on a Persuasion roll. One roll may be attempted each day if they care to.</p>\n<p>Until the characters succeed she insults them, punches and kicks anyone who comes near her, and tries to alert passing ships to her plight by waving, screaming, and setting fire to things. Make her the passenger from hell.</p>\n<p>If treated well she develops a romantic interest in one of the characters. This sets up the perfect opportunity for her to be kidnapped by Kieran agents sometime in the future.</p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_53dtyb3i8lp","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/2. Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"M8psGt43gogLJPSh","name":"Plot Point Campaign","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Plot Point Campaign</h1>\n<h2>Threads</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>One of the ships that they find and raid has the name of some cyrans carved into it. It was Squibbed at some point.</li>\n<li>Mention Tidewater Rock</li>\n<li>Mention the Council of Princes</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Plot Points</h2>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Welcome to the Sotrm Reaver:</strong> The scoundrals start with an evening in Port Verge. Wake up press ganged in the <em>Storm Reaver</em>. Are assigned roles, and then watch a good keelhauling. <em>Day 1 from The Wormwood Mutiny</em></li>\n<li><strong>Day in the life of a pirate: </strong>The scoundrals are bullied by some crew sent my Master Scourge. A few days later they are sent to deal with the bilges. A brawl with owlbear. <em>Day 2, Day4, and Day 5 from The Wormwood Mutiny</em></li>\n<li><strong>Storm at Sea:</strong> The scoundrals have to survive a storm at sea on the <em>Storm Reaver</em>. <em>Day 8 from the Wormwood Mutiny</em></li>\n<li><strong>Pirate Duties:</strong> The scoundrals have a few series of encounters. Gathering some crabs for the captain. Training for boarding. Unpleasant duties and attack in the bilges. <em>Day 11, day 14, Day 17, and Day 19 from the Wormwood Mutiny</em></li>\n<li><strong>The Man's Promise:</strong> The crew of the <em>Storm Reaver</em> attacks and takes over the Man's Promise. The scoundrals are assigned to the skeleton crew. <em>Day 20 and 21 from the Wormwood Mutiny</em></li>\n<li><strong>Whisper's of Mutiny:</strong> Things go grim for the Man's Promise crew. The ship is caught in a Storm and shipwrecked. <em>Day 1 to 5 from the Wormwood Mutiny</em></li>\n<li><strong>Bonewrack Isle:</strong> Exploring Bonewrack Isle and rescue crew members from the grindylows. <em>Bonewrack Isle from the Wormwood Mutiny</em></li>\n<li><strong>Mutiny!:</strong> The scoundrals mutiny against Mister Dabrak and take over the Man's Promise. <em>Mutiny from the Wormwood Mutiny</em></li>\n<li><strong>Hiding the Evidence!:</strong> The scoundrals take the Man's Promise to Rickety' Squibs to disguise their ship and recristen it. <em>Hiding the Evidence from Raiders of the Fever Sea</em></li>\n<li><strong>Landlubber Trap:</strong> The scoundrals encounter a ship that has been set as a trap by Sauaghin. <em>Event 11: Hook, Line, and Sinkerfrom Piracy on the Fever Sea from Raiders of the Fever Sea</em></li>\n<li><strong>Cracking Tidewater Rock:</strong> The scoundrals find a base of operations by gaining control of Tidewater Rock. <em>Tidewater Rock from Raiders of the Fever Sea</em></li>\n<li><strong>Raid on the Rock:</strong> (Required Landlubber Trap) The scoundrals find a base of operations by gaining control of Tidewater Rock. (perhaps use Attack on Brigandy Bay pg 147 for some ideas on how to conduct the fight) <em>Combined Event 16 and 17 from Raiders of the Fever Sea</em></li>\n<li><strong>Treasure Hunting in Mancatching Cove:</strong> The scoundrals sail to mancatcher cove and battle the Sahuaghin there to gain the treasure that has been left there. <em>The Treasure of Mancatacher Cove from Raiders of the Fever Sea</em></li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Savage Tales</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Sea Wolves:</strong> The scoundrals commit an act of priacy on the hazaar Seas. <em>Event 7 from Piracy on the fever Sea from Raiders of the Fever Sea</em></li>\n<li><strong>Raiding Settlements:</strong> The scoundrals may commit land raids on sea-side settlements. <em>Event 8: Low-Hanging Fruit from Piracy on the fever Sea from Raiders of the Fever Sea</em></li>\n<li><strong>Upon the Famished Mane:</strong> The scoundrals encounter a pirate ship being burned by a Karrnathi warship. <em>Event 10: Upon the Famished Mane from Piracy on the Fever Sea from Raiders of the Fever Sea</em></li>\n<li><strong>No Honor Among Thieves:</strong> This savage tale occurs as the scoundrals come upon an attack by another pirate ship already underway. The PCs first sight the battle from a mile away and come upon it just as the pirates have disabled the merchant ship and now prepare to board her. <em>Event 13: No Honor Among Thieves from Piracy on the Fever Sea from Raiders of the Fever Sea</em></li>\n<li><strong>The Frying Pan:</strong> The scoundrals encounter a Karrn or Brelish pirate hunter. <em>Event 13: The Frying Pan from Piracy on the Fever Sea from Raiders of the Fever Sea</em></li>\n<li><strong>For Whom the Bell Tolls:</strong> This savage tale takes place over three successive nights when the scoundrals are out of sight of the nearest shore. It always occurs in the waning hours of the day as the sun sinks below the horizon, as they are stalked and attacked by a ghost ship. <em>Event 14: For Whom the Bell Tolls from Piracy on the Fever Sea from Raiders of the Fever Sea</em></li>\n<li><strong>Hijack the Immortal:</strong> The scoundrals are highered by someone to hijack a powerful warship. <em>Hijack the Immortal pg 140 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n<li><strong>Debauchery:</strong> The scoundrals are approached by a vengeful father to assassinate someone who has defiled his daughter. <em>Debauchery pg 141 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n<li><strong>The Terror:</strong> Can the scoundrals rescue a unwilling shipwright from service on Prince Rhygers secret vessel. <em>The Terror pg 151 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n<li><strong>Treasure for the Taking:</strong> The scoundrals are lead to some buried treasure by Stumpy Pete (Stumpy Pete perhaps works at Rickety Squibs). <em>Treasure for the Taking pg 154 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n<li><strong>The Low Down:</strong> The scoundrals find a dinghy at seas, they rescue one of the most ruthless pirates in the Lhazaar Seas. <em>The Low Down pg 156 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n<li><strong>The Butcher:</strong> (Requires The Low Down) The scoundrals find a ship with sailors horribly butchered. If they set off in persuit they find the man they rescued. What will the scoundrals do? <em>The Butcher pg 156 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n<li><strong>Big for Freedom:</strong> The scoundrals are asked to save a salve girl serving at a tavern in a port town? <em>Bid for Freedom pg 160 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n<li><strong>Revenge:</strong> (Could be used to turn against the Seadragons??) When the scoundrals try to sell some treasure, and item is noticed by a heartbroken lover. He asks for help with revenge? <em>Revenge pg 173 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n<li><strong>The Dragonshard Ship:</strong> The scoundrals are asked to help a fellow pirate with some piracy, but find it better guarded than thought. <em>The Iron Ship pg 173 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n<li><strong>False Kidnapping:</strong> The scoundrals are asked by a noble to stage a fake kidnapping. This a noble tale to help save a daughter from a poor marriage. <em>False Kidnapping pg 176 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n<li><strong>The Black Prince:</strong> The scoundrals are asked by a ghost to help put him to rest. <em>The Black Prince pg 177 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n<li><strong>A Toast to Death:</strong> The scoundrals are tasked with smuggling wine to on of the princes. Unknown to them the wine is poisoned. Use this Savage Tale to frame the party and create bad relations with other pirates.  <em>A Toast to Death pg 173 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n<li>sadfsdf</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Encounters</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Night Swimmers:</strong> During the evening the ship is attacked by a group of Sahuaghin. <em>Event 6 include from Piracy on the Fever Sea from Raiders of the Fever Sea</em></li>\n<li><strong>Wreck of the Carcanus:</strong> Use as a idea for the scounrals aquiring magical sails for their ship. <em>Wreck of Carcanus pg 150 from 50 Fathoms Explorer</em></li>\n</ul>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":7},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_0gxlbqom8dl","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/1. Mourners of Lhazaar Plot Point","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"MfxQEJpAFYnCf2JW","name":"Krornik \"Fishguts\" Kragshard","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<p>Most people think Krornik “Fishguts” Kragshard gets his nickname from the stains on his apron or the contents of his infamous stew, but few know he earned the sobriquet as a competitive eater in the low bars of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport}. As a young man, it was said that Kragshard could eat more of anything, and faster, than anyone. Folks still talk about the night that Kragshard devoured an entire bucket of boiled eggs in the Salty Swab by the docks.</p>\n<p>Kragshard was trained as a professional chef at the Lobster’s Armor, one of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport}’s most popular (and expensive) restaurants, but when he was thrown out for inappropriate behavior with his assistant, he ended up plying his trade with several sailing vessels in the Lhazaar before embarking on Captain Rockface’s <em>Storm Reaver</em>, where he has served as ship’s cook for the past 3 years.</p>\n<p>An affable fellow, Kragshard loves his food, and has more recently developed a taste for rum, a habit that’s only encouraged by Cut-Throat Grok, the <em>Storm Reaver's</em> quartermaster and Kragshard’s best friend aboard the ship.</p>\n<p>Sadly for Kragshard, his drinking led him to bet his own life against Prince Rockface in a card game one drunken night 2 years ago. Kragshard lost, and his life became Rockface’s to do with what he would. Rockface now thinks as little of Kragshard as he does a bilge rat, but he’s not yet killed the cook because drunk as he is, Kragshard is still a better cook than anyone else on the <em>Storm Reaver</em>, and the captain is partial to his cooking.</p>\n<p>Kragshard’s days begin with blearily handing out ship’s biscuits to the crew on deck before retiring to the galley to prepare the evening meal (almost always fish stew) in a big pot. Then he cozies up with a bottle of rum (sometimes mixed with raw eggs) and waits for the rest of the day to pass. Nevertheless, Kragshard is a skilled chef, though few of the crew beyond the captain and his officers ever get the chance to sample Kragshard’s more palatable fare.</p>\n<p>His only joy, aside from drinking and swapping yarns with Grok, are his chickens. Kragshard loves his poultry and collects any rare breeds he comes across. Anyone with a background in farming finds Kragshard friendly, while those who truly know their birds quickly discover a helpful friend. Kragshard’s favorite bird, a large black cockerel named Black-Hearted Bezebel, often perches on the cook’s shoulder and even talks to him, or so Kragshard occasionally drunkenly claims.</p>\n<h3>Appearance</h3>\n<p>Kragshard is a large, some would say fat, man, weighing well over 200 pounds and standing only 5 feet tall. He exudes an air of neglect, perhaps even despair, from the bushy tufts of black hair behind his ears, to his rotting teeth, to the stains on his filthy apron. He walks with a wallowing waddle, particularly when drunk, but is capable of surprising acts of strength. Kragshard talks with a thick Shackles accent, which some people find hard to follow. He’s had so many lashes that his back is like tanned leather, and he claims to not even feel the bite of the lash anymore. After 44 years in the school of hard knocks, Kragshard is a man who clearly cares little for himself or what people think of him. Nevertheless, he is at heart a kind man, and does his best to protect his cook’s mate from punishments brought on by mistakes made by either of them.</p>\n<h3>Gossip</h3>\n<p>The PCs can learn the following about Kragshard with successful Diplomacy checks to gather information.</p>\n<p>DC 5: “Fishguts” might once have been a famous chef at that fancy place in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport}, but now all he cooks is fishgut stew. He’s so pickled in rum now, bilgewater is all he can make.</p>\n<p>DC 10: Remember the last cook’s mate? Nobody does—only when he disappeared. Just up and vanished, that one, like he was spirited away, or maybe dropped in a pot...</p>\n<p>DC 15: Kragshard was so drunk once that he bet his life in a game with the captain, and now he’s little more than Rockface’s slave.</p>\n<h3>CampaiGn Role</h3>\n<p>Krornik Kragshard begins the adventure as a cynical, washed up drunk who is insensibly intoxicated half of the time, dreaming of a better life. However, he is also an obvious potential friend and ally of the PCs, as he loathes the captain and crew of the <em>Storm Reaver</em> and longs for a chance to escape. Kragshard makes an excellent NPC to plant the idea of mutiny in the PCs’ minds. He is not a risktaker, however, and can, like Sandara Quinn (see page 56), act as a voice of reason as the PCs plan their actions. If the PCs manage to befriend Kragshard, he can become a useful ally for the PCs in the future. Besides being a fine cook, he has handy communication skills and can also help out in a fight if needed. Kragshard has also plied his trade in the Shackles throughout his life and has an excellent knowledge of the region and its perils, personalities, and possibilities.</p>\n<p>As the adventure progresses, Kragshard’s interactions with the PCs begin to give his life purpose, to the extent that by the time the PCs move to the Man’s Promise in Part Two, he begins drinking much less. Away from the sour atmosphere of the <em>Storm Reaver</em>, Kragshard’s spirits lighten, and he is only drunk 1 day in every four. When the PCs finally mutiny, Kragshard is sober for the event, and aids the PCs as best he can. If the mutiny is successful, Kragshard announces that his new friends have inspired him to turn over a new leaf. If the PCs are cutthroats, Kragshard throws his lot in with them to begin a new life. If they are kindhearted dandies, Kragshard sees in them a more honorable way of life. Regardless, he offers his services as ship’s cook to the PCs. His lapses into drinking become less frequent—he is now drunk only 1 day in every week—and continue to be so throughout the rest of the Adventure Path.</p>\n<p>It is unlikely that the PCs will make an enemy of Kragshard, but should they do so, he gladly assists anyone who wants to kill the PCs. Having had a taste of possible freedom, he wants to punish those who let him taste it before he crawls back into the bottom of a rum bottle to die.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"monks-enhanced-journal":{"type":"base","_viewcount":3,"role":"Ship's Cook","location":"The Wormwood","race":"Male Dwarf","gender":"","age":"","eyes":"","skin":"","hair":"","profession":"","voice":"","faction":"","height":"","weight":"","traits":"","ideals":"","bonds":"","flaws":"","longterm":"","shortterm":"","beliefs":"","secret":"","DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":{"notes":""},"scrollPos":"{\".description\":50}"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_wu5utkhw5ta","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Crew of the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"N9YPOpmxldrvkLkh","name":"Forecastle","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Forecastle</h1>\n<p>This raised deck stands some 10 feet above the main deck, immediately behind the bowsprit, which is shaped like a rearing dragon spitting lightning. The foremast rises 30 feet above this deck.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_e26boiu8etj","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"OFdQGATN7TtJNvRX","name":"01 Welcome to the Storm Reaver","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Welcome to the Storm Reaver</h1>\n<p>The pirates wake up the in the hold of Prince Rockface's the <em>Storm Reaver</em> of the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Cloudreaver Principality]{Cloudreaver Principality}. They all remember the night before, but they all blacked out at some point. The pirates awake feeling groggy like they are still hung over. Before the pirates can do much more than sit up, Master Scourge enters the hold to wake them and get them up to the main deck. Six rough-looking <em>Storm Reaver</em> pirates, armed with saps, accompany him. An expression that might be mistaken for pain but which is clearly an attempt at a smile bruises Scourge's face as he cracks the whip in his hand and screams at newcomers.</p>\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“Still abed with the sun over the yardarm? On your feet, ye filthy swabs! Get up on deck and report for duty afore Prince Rockface flays your flesh into sausage skins and has Fishguts fry ye up for breakfast!”</p>\n</aside>\n<p>The pirates quickly discover that most, if not all, of their weapons and equipment are gone. If the any refuse, even momentarily, to accompany Scourge, he lashes out at any offender with his whip. If necessary, he calls for aid from his crew, who attack uncooperative characters with their saps. It should be immediately clear that if they don't cooperate, they will quickly be overpowered. </p>\n<p><strong>Development:</strong> If the pirates decide to fight, Master Scourge and his pirates attack subduing them. The <em>Storm Reaver</em> pirates will not the kill the new comers, however. Once they have the upper hand, they will take the offender—conscious or unconscious—to the main deck, where they get an immediate taste of @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Punishments]{punishment} on the <em>Storm Reaver</em>. The offenders are tied to the mainmast, and Master Scourge gives each of them three lashes before the captain's address.</p>\n<p class=\"example\"><strong>Skill Check:</strong> On the way to the upper deck, have the pirates make notice checks. On a <strong>success </strong>they hear someone making oinking sounds and talking soothingly to was sounds like a pig. On a raise someon hears the rattle of a chain, and a slight whimper.</p>\n<h2>Meeting the Captain</h2>\n<p>Once on the main deck it's quickly apparent that they are on a sizable ship in the middle of the ocean, far from any land. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Greentarn]{Greentarn} are just an ochre haze many miles astern. Figures cluster around the ship's mainmast, looking up at the higher deck on the stern, where two figures stand, Prince Rockface and First Mate Mister Lagraa.</p>\n<p>There are three other recruits are standing with them on the deck, set apart by their relative cleanliness and their apparent unease with their newfound situation. The other three were picked up in Elysium, Sandara Quinn, Rosie Cusswell, and Conchobhar Turlach Dalian. A dozen or so other pirates stand about on the deck or in the ship's rigging. Once everyone is on the main deck, the captain speaks.</p>\n<aside class=\"sidebar read-aloud\">\n<p>“Glad you could join us at last! Welcome to the <em>Storm Reaver</em>! My thanks for ‘volunteering' to join my crew. I'm Mika Rockface. That's Prince Rockface to you filthy lot, not that you'll ever need to address me. I have only one rule—don't speak to me. I like talk, but I don't like your talk. Follow that rule and we'll all get along fine.</p>\n<p>“Oh, and one more thing. Even with you new recruits, we're still short-handed, and I aim to keep what crew I have. There'll be a keelhaulin' for anyone caught killin' anyone. Mr. Lagraa! If you'd be so kind as to make pirates out of these landlubbers, it'll save me having to put them in the sweatbox for a year and a day before I make pies out of 'em.”</p>\n</aside>\n<h2>Job Assignments</h2>\n<p>After some recent difficulties, the <em>Storm Reaver </em>is undermanned and there are some roles that need to be filled. Mister Lagraa first is looking for a new rigger. The scoundrals are all required to climb to the crows nest.</p>\n<p class=\"example\"><strong>Dramatic Task</strong> This will require 3 round Dramtic Task. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} checks are the only skilled allowed. The pirate with the most success tokens is the winner is that they are now a rigger and work directly for Mister Lagraa. Anyone caught deliberately trying to fail the test will be immediately given three lashes as @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Punishments]{punishment}.</p>\n<p>Lagraa's second test is one of necessity—he knows the ship's cook, Krornik “Fishguts” Kragshard, has a drinking problem, and he's fed up with eating rubbish. This test is simple: Lagraa asks each pirate in turn whether they can cook, and if one of them says yes, theybecoe the new cook's mate. If Lagraa gets to the end of the line without an affirmative answer, he simply picks the fattest pirate (Lagraa assumes that character likes food the most) and says, “You're a cook's mate now,” and tells that PC to report to Krornik Kragshard in the galley. If more than one person claims to be a good cook, Lagraa picks the fattest.</p>\n<p>The remaining pirates are all assigned to be swabs, under the command of Master Scourge, who immediately gets them working. </p>\n<p>Review @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.A Pirate's Day]{A Pirate's Day} and @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Board Actions]{Ship Board Actions} to find out more what the pirates do during the day. Check the entry on @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Krornik Kragshard]{Krornik Kragshard} for interactions on the first day with Fishguts.</p>\n<h2>Friendly Face</h2>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Sandara Quinn]{Sandara Quinn} has managed to convince @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Cut-Throat Grok]{Cut-Throat Grok} to return her personal equipment, claiming the itesm were righteous artifacts blessed by @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Arawai]{Arawai} that would bring a terrible curse on those who wrongfully held them. This morning she managed to acquire two items of the new crew members, items that they would struggle without the use of. At some point on this first day she will approach the new comers as soon as she can to return equipment and offer her friendship. She can explain the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>It is not what you know but who you know on a pirate ship. Friends help each other out, enemies cause trouble.</li>\n<li>She knows Prince Mika is upset as they have not had a very successful outting at sea, and once again she couldn't crack Tidewater Rock.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>A Keelhauling</h2>\n<p><strong>Work:</strong> The pirates spend the day at their assigned jobs. In addition, each pirates can take a single daytime ship action.</p>\n<p><strong>“Bloody Hour”:</strong> The crew gathers on deck at dusk to witness the keelhauling of Jakes Magpie, a pirate caught stealing from the quartermaster's store the night before. After a brief interrogation at the hands of Mr. Lagraa and Master Scourge, Jakes admitted his crime, and is now brought up from the @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Bilges]{bilges} to be slowly keelhauled before the evening meal. A successful @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} can see the relish with which Mr. Lagraa, in particular, tugs at the rope as the unfortunate Magpie is dragged under the ship. What appears on the other side has been cut to shreds and is soon thrown overboard to feed the sharks.</p>\n<p>A pirate who examines the body before it is dumped can make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} check to estimate that the unfortunate Jakes took significant damage from the punishment and drowned as well. Witnessing Jakes's keelhauling should help impress upon the pirates the deadly nature of pirate punishments.</p>\n<p><strong>Leisure:</strong> After dinner and the rum rations, various @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Crew Entertainment]{pirate entertainments} take place on @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Main Deck]{deck}, in the @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Weapons Deck]{weapons deck} or the @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Mess Hall]{mess hall}, for as long as people are sober enough to participate. In addition, each pirate can take a single nighttime @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Board Actions]{ship action}.</p>\n<p><strong>Rest:</strong> Provided they've drunk their @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Grog Ration]{rum rations}, the pirates can retire to their hammocks in the @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Weapons Deck]{weapons deck} whenever they wish. The pirates can take additional nighttime @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Board Actions]{ship actions} if they have the energy.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":false,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.6\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_0gxlbqom8dl","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/1. Mourners of Lhazaar Plot Point","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"OUy9aEU385EhSEt6","name":"#[CF_tempEntity]","content":"","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0gxlbqom8dl","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/1. Mourners of Lhazaar Plot Point","color":"#000000","name":"1. Mourners of Lhazaar Plot Point","children":["OFdQGATN7TtJNvRX","U6QtUVBcJ3kCOUrn","Unf9BdNknxxW8NJc","276jgwCRrWKYcf0I","565axwczkrQNYLJU","fitTepd1kSfxudlF","jFJFL5sly5U5OGOF","M8psGt43gogLJPSh"],"folderPath":["temp_bmn52t4oyo"]}}}
{"_id":"PH5sEmqgrKISoHfZ","name":"Revenge!","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Revenge!</h1>\n<p>No matter where the group tries to sell the necklace in Shark Bay a masaquani local, Yan Yort, oversees the sale. Without warning he lunges at the character holding the necklace, crying out,</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“Murderer! Where did you get that?”</p>\n</section>\n<p>Yan doesn’t draw a weapon and should be easy to subdue.</p>\n<p>Once he has been restrained Yan breaks down.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“I gave that necklace to my girlfriend last year. She vanished two months ago. She had secretly been seeing a visitor by the name of Marcus Royal. I found out a few months ago after following her one night, but I didn’t mind. I loved her. One night she never came back. I assumed she’d left me for Royal. Please, tell me where you found it?”</p>\n</section>\n<p>After listening to the heroes’ tale Yan’s face tightens.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“She would never have thrown it away. She knew how much it was worth. Royal must have killed her! I’ll give you 1,000 pieces of eight if you help me kill him.”</p>\n</section>\n<p>Royal did indeed kill the woman. She fell in love with him but Royal only wanted her for her body. After a vicious argument Royal stabbed her and threw her body in the lagoon. She had never shown him the necklace, but kept it hidden in her dress.</p>\n<p>Yan knows Royal spends most of his time in the Wench and Tankard tavern near the docks. Attacking Royal in the tavern is too risky—he has many friends—but once he leaves for his ship he is fair game. If Yan dies in the fight the heroes find $300 on his person.</p>\n<p> Yan Yort (195): Typical Pirate.</p>\n<p>Pirates (41): 40 Typical Pirates and Marcus Royal, a Wild Card Veteran Pirate (p. 195).</p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_53dtyb3i8lp","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/2. Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Q687UTK8tTH8uc8s","name":"Quarter Deck","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Quarter Deck</h1>\n<p>This raised deck stands 15 feet above the main deck. The ship’s bridge is here and holds the ship’s wheel. The wheel is 3 feet across and has 10 spokes decorated with silver inlays, its bolts carved to resemble kraken heads.</p>\n<p><span style=\"color:#3598db\">Prince Rockface</span> and <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Mr. Lagraa </span>spend most of their time on this deck. When the captain is on deck, the poop deck and quarter deck are off-limits to everyone but officers.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L91WkUzg75E8tVjM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_e26boiu8etj","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"QygQfqdlw5zh5IkL","name":"Ship Punishments","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Ship Punishments</h1>\n<p>To maintain the obedience and effectiveness of their crews, most captains enforce strict schedules and shipboard laws upon their vessels, all maintained by the swift dispensation of brutal punishments. The following presents (in order of severity) the game effects of a variety of typical nautical punishments, which the pirates have the potential to face or inflict during their piratical careers. Most of these sentences are meted out just before the evening meal, at an event typically referred to as the bloody hour. Victims are tied to the whipping post on the main deck and their backs stripped for punishment—with penalties doubled for those who resist. </p>\n<h3>Rope Bash</h3>\n<p>Little more than an admonishment—and occasionally used as a sign of endearment—a rope bash is a single attack with the hefty, sealed end of a ship’s rope.</p>\n<h3>The Lash</h3>\n<p>This is an attack using a whip. Lashes during bloody hour require a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Vigor} check (+1) for every three lashes or cause one level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.</p>\n<h3>Cat-o’-Nine-Tails</h3>\n<p>This is an attack using a cat-o’-ninetails, also referred to simply as a cat—lashes with the cat require a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Vigor} check (–1) one level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} for every three strikes.</p>\n<h3>Confined in the Sweatbox</h3>\n<p>A cramped metal box left on deck and exposed to the sun, a sweatbox is terribly confining and replicates unbearably hot conditions. Each four hours in the sweatbox the victim must make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Vigor} check or suffer a level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}. There is a –1 to this check for each 8 hours they spend in the sweat box. Any creature with fire resistance is immune to the effects of the sweatbox. Victims typically spend 8, 12 or even 24 hours locked up in the sweatbox.</p>\n<h3>Keelhauling</h3>\n<p>The most frightful of pirate punishments is keelhauling, as it generally ends in death—often by decapitation. Being keelhauled involves being tied to a rope looped over a ship’s keel and dragged down one side of a ship, underwater across the barnacle encrusted hull, and up the other side. Keelhauling can be done either fast or slow. If done fast, the barnacles cut deep and flense the victim, dealing 2d6 points of damage per round. If done slow, shallower cuts are incurred, dealing 1d6 damage per round, but the risk of drowning increases. How long keelhauling takes typically depends on the vessel, with a keelhauling on a ship like the <em>Storm Reaver</em> taking 6 rounds if done fast and 12 rounds if done slow.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_f5h8exvluwf","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Ship lore","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Sc8zngwHZvU5mmmY","name":"Boarding School","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Boarding School</h1>\n<p> </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_5m4g64zt3jr","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/3. Aboard the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"TFDAsNf5ym4DG8jL","name":"The Butcher","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">The Butcher</h1>\n<p>Ideally, several months should pass between this adventure and the events of  The Low Down (157).</p>\n<p>The heroes spy a frigate drifting in the wind, her masts smashed and sails tattered. Drawing near, the group sees signs of a recent and bloody battle—several large holes are clearly visible in her side and corpses litter the splintered, bloodsoaked deck.</p>\n<p>As the heroes watch, a lone figure staggers onto the deck from the rear cabins. Spying them, the figure tries to reach the side of ship, waving frantically as he lurches forward. He barely makes half a dozen steps before he falls lifeless to the planks.</p>\n<p>On boarding, the heroes discover a scene of absolute carnage. A successful Common Knowledge roll reveals most of the injuries were not inflicted in battle. Most of the corpses have been horribly mutilated in some way. Characters failing a Fear check are violently sick and gain a level of Fatigue which is only recovered 30 minutes after leaving the Conquistador.</p>\n<h3>The Survivor</h3>\n<p>The survivor is unconscious and badly bleeding. Both of his hands have been severed at the wrists and his nose has been hacked off. A successful Healing roll staunches the blood flow and returns the man to consciousness. Once awake, he tells his tale.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“My name is Jim Black, ship’s cook. Pirates attacked us barely two hours ago. Having no escort, the captain saw fit to surrender, planning on trading the cargo for our lives. He assembled us on the deck and raised a flag of surrender. The swines raked the deck with grapeshot before boarding.</p>\n<p>“The captain offered his cargo without a struggle but the pirate captain shot him on the spot. They took the cargo but they had no intention of letting us live. The pirate captain had every man butchered—gutted some, amputated limbs off others, and even made some of them eat their own body parts.</p>\n<p>“That devil hacked off my nose and tried to make me eat it. I put on a brave face, hoping he’d show mercy if I didn’t beg, and said it needed pepper. He asked my trade, and when I told him he hacked my hands off and left me here to die. What use am I now with no hands, eh? There’s still cargo below if you want it—I’m not going to put up a fight.”</p>\n</section>\n<p>Jim describes the pirate captain. Any character who took part in  The Low Down (157) and makes a Common Knowledge roll recognizes the man as the mariner they rescued. Jim adds that the pirate ship was a galleon called the Mad Dog and it sailed away east.</p>\n<p>Below deck are two cargo spaces worth of food—Low’s ship lacked room to store the entire cargo.</p>\n<h3>Hunting the Mad Dog</h3>\n<p>If the heroes decline the cargo and set off immediately, the Mad Dog has a three-hour lead. Taking the Conquistador’s cargo increases the lead to six hours. How much head start Low has is irrelevant—but don’t tell the group.</p>\n<p>Believing the Conquistador’s crew to be dead, Low is in no rush to escape. Riding hard with the wind, the heroes spy a sail on the horizon shortly before dusk. Use the standard Chase rules. When the ships draw level, Low recognizes the heroes as his rescuers and shouts across to them.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“Well strike me down! I never thought I’d see you fine chaps again. I have no beef with you lads—you did get me a good turn and that’s a rare thing. I’ll return the favor now—turn sail and run ‘n I’ll let you go in peace. Continue your present course and I’ll watch you eat your own lips as you beg for mercy.”</p>\n</section>\n<p>Low will actually let the heroes sail away in peace if they choose to turn around. Should they cross his path a second time he has no hesitation about killing them—he considers the favor repaid in full. Of course, he’ll also take great delight in boarding their ship and cutting off their lips if they try to slug it out.</p>\n<p>If the group loses the fight and surrenders, Low does indeed cut off their lips, as well as their ears and noses—each character gains the Ugly Hindrance—before letting them go as a warning to others.</p>\n<h3>The Mad Dog (Galleon)</h3>\n<p>Acc/Top Speed: 2/12; Travel Speed: 3; Handling: –3; Toughness: 20(4); Crew: 30+40; Cargo Space: 6; Guns: 20 Notes: Heavy Armor; Low has sacrificed cargo space for additional cannons.</p>\n<p>Pirates (65): 60 Pirates and five Veteran Pirate officers (p. 195).</p>\n<p>Booty: A King’s Ransom aboard the Mad Dog. Among the treasure is a golden triangle engraved with unintelligible writing. The hold contains four units of food and two units of gunpowder.</p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_53dtyb3i8lp","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/2. Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"U6QtUVBcJ3kCOUrn","name":"02 Life Aboard the Storm Reaver","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Life Aboard the Storm Reaver</h1>\n<p>Each day aboard the Storm Reaver the swabs will be assigned a task from their corresponding task list as outlined in @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.A Pirate's Day]{A Pirate's Day}. The swabs will be allowed @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Board Actions]{Ship Board Actions} one per day and one per night as outlined in those rules.</p>\n<p>Each day consists of</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Wake up</li>\n<li>Ship tack for breakfast</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.A Pirate's Day]{Daily assignments}</li>\n<li>Possible @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Board Actions]{daily ship action}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Punishments]{Bloody Hour}</li>\n<li>Evening @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Grog Ration]{Grog Ration} and evening meal</li>\n<li>Possible @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Board Actions]{nightly ship action}</li>\n<li>Bedtime and/or further @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Board Actions]{nightly ship action}</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>As Time Goes By</h2>\n<p>The following events should be played approxiately around these days:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Day 2: @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Laying Down the Law]{Laying Down the Law}</li>\n<li>Day 4: @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Something in the Bilges]{Something in the Bilges}</li>\n<li>Day 5: @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Fight with the Owlbear]{Fight with the Owlbear}, heavy rain starts in the evening</li>\n<li>Day 6: Building storm (–1 on all rigging checks for the day)</li>\n<li>Day 7: @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.The Storm on the Storm Reaver]{The Storm on the Storm Reaver}</li>\n<li>Day 8: Weakening storm (–1 on all rigging checks for the day)</li>\n<li>Day 10: @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Trouble in the Sun]{Trouble in the Sun}</li>\n<li>Day 12: @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Boarding School]{Boarding School}</li>\n<li>Day 13 on: Unpleasant Duties. At this point Mr. Lagraa and Master Scourge have had enough of the swabs and from this point forward give the swabs all the shit jobs that they hate the most. Any pirate not at least Friendly with the swabs has thier reaction decreased by one. Mister Lagraa has been completely turned by Master Scourge and makes more appearances and takes more of a focus on the swabs at this point.</li>\n<li>Day 13 and 14: Cold front strikes (–1 on all checks to avoid @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{fatigue})</li>\n<li>Day 15: @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Risky Games in the Bilges]{Risky Games in the Bilges}</li>\n<li>Day 16: @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.03 Attacking the Majestic Griffon]{Attacking the Majestic Griffon}</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Mister Lagraa and Master Scourge</h2>\n<p>Frequent interactions and run-ins should happen mainly with Master Scourge, though Mr. Lagraa should also be made into a villian. But she has more things to occupy her time. Master Scourage might also use some of cronies to also harass the swabs. These might include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Gragoth]{Gragoth}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Patch \"Salty\" Kolkrinun]{Patch \"Salty\" Kolkrinun}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Sador Chumlett]{Sador Chumlett}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Maheem]{Maheem}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Slippery Syl]{Slippery Syl}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Jaundiced Sudak]{Jaundiced Sudak}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Tam \"Narwhal\" Tate]{Tam \"Narwhal\" Tate}</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Experiences to make happen</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Pirates can make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} check to assertain the location of the <em>Storm Reaver</em>. Modifiers depend on the location of the ship.</li>\n<li>Talk to Trucco about his past experience being Press Ganged and the items he might have about getting gear back.</li>\n<li>Have someone run into @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Rosie Cusswell]{Rosie Cusswell} after seeing Grok. She is upset at her inability to get back her Fiddle.</li>\n<li>Crimson Cogs might want to encounter Torlan after his tale the night before.</li>\n<li>Roll every time Daina is in the Galley about what she might find within the Galley on the @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tables.Galley Finds]{Galley Finds} table.</li>\n<li>Have someone see @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Hakrilli Quarne]{Hakrilli Quarne} and @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Grovus Stormbread]{Grovus Stormbread} in a strong arguement about the arcane.</li>\n<li>Daina should encounter @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.\"Caulky\" Tarron]{\"Caulky\" Tarron} food tasting, with an opportunity to notice that she might have been at the Tavern the night they where Press ganged.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_0gxlbqom8dl","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/1. Mourners of Lhazaar Plot Point","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Unf9BdNknxxW8NJc","name":"03 Attacking the Majestic Griffon","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Attacking the Majestic Griffon</h1>\n<h3>Ambience</h3>\n<p>Although the swabs have only a relatively small part to play in this fight, try to give your players a cinematic experience of the battle. Describe the noises of fighting that drift out of the mist, which occasionally parts to give the swabs a glimpse of the larger battle. As pirates and sailors fall or are thrown into the sea, let the swabs hear their screams as they’re ripped apart by sharks. Finally, describe the hush that falls over the two ships as the battle finally nears its end.</p>\n<h3>Hold the quarterdeck</h3>\n<p>As the <em>Storm Reaver</em> closes to within half a mile of the <em>Majestic Griffon</em>, Riaris Krine summons the swabs to the <em>Storm Reaver's</em> poop deck to give them their task for the upcoming battle.</p>\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“The ship’s wheel is on the aft deck, just below the sterncastle. You’re going to grapple over, incapacitate the guards on the sterncastle, take the wheel, and guard the ship’s boats. Stop anyone who tries to get away on one of the boats. Don’t move from the wheel until the fighting’s done, or you’ll have to answer to me. Oh yeah, as we get close, it’s going to get foggy. Just stick to what I told you to do.”</p>\n</aside>\n<p>Krine puts the swab who performed best in the boarding training in charge of the boarding party, and issues any swab who still has not acquired a weapon a single weapon (excluding alchemist’s fire) from the @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Officer's Hall and Armory]{armory}.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Deception]{Deception} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} check:</strong> The PCs can make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Deception]{Deception} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} check to convince Krine of the importance of their mission and choose two other pirates to accompany them, but characters such as Grok, Kroop, and Owlbear are all busy elsewhere. The swabs can choose two hostile or unfriendly NPCs if they wish—people do die in battle after all.</p>\n<h3>The Sea</h3>\n<p>The captain orders Fishguts and the cook's mate to slaughter a pig and throw it overboard to attract sharks for the coming battle.</p>\n<p>If a sailor or pirate falls overboard there is a 1 in 3 chance each round that they are attacked by a Shark. Each time someone is attacked by a shark and but, another shark comes to the prey.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Shark]{Shark} (6)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Closing for Boarding</h3>\n<p>While the <em>Storm Reaver</em> closes for boarding the Arcane Cannon is fired and just before boarding a barrage of ballista's are fired at the prey. The swabs will have up to four rounds worth of actions to fire or cast spells on the other ship before the ships close enough for boarding. Each round there is a 40% chance the swab is attacked by a crossbow. </p>\n<p>After 4 rounds, the two ships collide, and the pirates begin hurling grapples and lowering planks to board the Majestic Griffon. The ships remain locked together until the battle ends.</p>\n<h3>Round 1: Boarding Action</h3>\n<p>The swabs must cross from the <em>Storm Reaver's</em> quarterdeck to the <em>Majestic Griffon's</em> aftcastle. 6 sailors guard the aftcastle plus the pilot.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Sailor]{Sailor} (6)</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Pilot]{Pilot} (1)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Round 3: The Prince's Back</h3>\n<p>At this point in the battle the fog parts, allowing the swabs to see Prince Mike Rockface, Riaris Krine, and Gragoth rushing towards the doors leading to the second deck below. Have the swabs make <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}</strong> checks. Those that succeed notice a sailor sneaking up behind Prince Rockface. Any warning will or attack will allow Rockface to turn to slay the sailor. Rockface looks up at the swab that provided any warning and nods in recognition. If the swabs don't warn the Prince, the sailor will strike a non-fatal blow from behind. Once slaying the sailor, Prince Rockface will look around and notices the swabs could have warned her.</p>\n<h3>Round 6: Fleeing Sailors</h3>\n<p>Three sailors appear out of the fog, hoping to release one of the ships boats and flee. They must make two <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}</strong> checks to release the boat and one to jump aboard.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Sailor]{Sailor} (3)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Round 7-10: The Battle Turns</h3>\n<p>Through the fog, the swabs can see the crew scattering or surrendering. Below, Prince Mika momentarily appears, gripping what appears to be a human heart in her hands.</p>\n<h3>Round 11: Abandoning Ship</h3>\n<p>The ships first mate and two sailors appear on the quarterdeck intent on fleeing in one of the ships boats.  Any successes from the prior effort make this easier.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Sailor]{Sailor} (2)</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.First Mate]{First Mate} (1)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Aftermath</h2>\n<p>The battle ends with the pirates victorious. The fog dissipates, and a line of prisoners from the Man’s Promise is paraded before Prince Rockface and the cheering crew of the <em>Storm Reaver</em>.</p>\n<p>Aboard the <em>Storm Reaver</em>, a party begins as the pirates celebrate their victory with fine food and drink from the <em>Majestic Griffon’s</em> hold. Prince Rockface holds a meeting with his top officers and divvies up the plunder from the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> among the crew in the early evening. Bolstered by gold and good drink, the party lasts for 36 hours, well into the next night. Naturally, no work takes place during the party. During this time, the swabs can take up to 5 ship actions of their choice, or do nothing but drink and revel like most of the pirate crew does.</p>\n<p><strong>Treasure:</strong> Each swab receives 150 gp in coinage as his or her share of the booty, modified by the following factors.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If the swabs took the aft deck and sterncastle within 6 rounds, they receive two @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Potion of Healing, Major]{Potion of Healing, Major} and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Potion of Invisibility, Minor]{Potion of Invisibility, Minor}, and each is awarded an additional 100 gp.</li>\n<li>If a swab warned Prince Rockface as he was being attacked in Round 3, the swabs receive an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Amulet of Natural Armor, Minor]{Amulet of Natural Armor, Minor}. If the swabs also killed the attacking sailor, they receive a short sword (accurate) as well.</li>\n<li>If the swabs did not warn the captain when he was being attacked, each swab receives only a half share of plunder (75 gp).</li>\n<li>For each sailor captured by the swabs, the swabs receive +25 gp to divide among themselves.</li>\n<li>If the swabs killed the First Mate in Round 11, they receive an additional 100 gp to divide among themselves. This reward increases to 200 gp if the swabs managed to capture the officer alive.</li>\n<li>For each pirate accidentally killed, deduct 150 gp from the party’s reward.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Development:</strong> If any swabs did not take part in the battle and are discovered, they are accused of cowardice and given a dozen lashes with the cat before the plunder is distributed. Such characters forfeit their share of the booty.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_0gxlbqom8dl","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/1. Mourners of Lhazaar Plot Point","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Vih1K90gKmHX1Qsa","name":"Officers Quarters","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Officers Quarters</h1>\n<p>These six cabins are the rooms of the some of the main officers of the Storm Reaver. Therooms are detailed clockwise from the upper left.</p>\n<h3>Officers Lockers</h3>\n<p>There are numerous lockers down here, one for each of the crew. Each locker can be picked with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check –1. Each locker contains [[/r 20d10]] in sovereigns and [[/r 2d10]] in galifars. Additionally they contain [[/r 1d3+1]] items from the @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tables.Crew Lockers]{Crew Lockers} table. The crew generally refers to this cache as their duffle.</p>\n<h3>Gragoth's Room</h3>\n<p> </p>\n<h3>Mister Lagraa's Room</h3>\n<p> </p>\n<h3>Master Scourge's Room</h3>\n<p>Prince Rockface does not have a strong liking to Master Scourge. As such the Boatswain has been given the smallest officers cabin.</p>\n<h3>Grovus Stormbeard's Room</h3>\n<p> </p>\n<h3>Hakrilli Quarne's Room</h3>\n<p> </p>\n<h3>Riaris Krine's Room</h3>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L91WkUzg75E8tVjM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_e26boiu8etj","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"W1qgHLJx4F2O2uXJ","name":"Captain's Cabin","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Captain's Cabin</h1>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Prince Mika Rockface]{Prince Mika Rockface's} cabin is richly decorated, its walls covered with intricate carvings depicting krakens devouring whales. Portholes along the port and starboard walls allow light to drift in, while to the aft lie windows and a door to a balcony. A bed that can double as a navigational or dining table when the mattress is rolled up sits against the starboard bulkhead with a chest to one side. Rich carpets appoint the floor. A desk is against the port wall with charts, navigational equipment, and writting materials scattered across it. Another chest is to the side of the desk.</p>\n<p>The chests are looked with a good lock (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check –2). The chest next to the bed contains <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Prince Rockface’s</span> personal possessions, while the chest next to the desk includes various books, personal itesm and a selection of nautical charts (which grant a +1 bonus to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Navigation]{Navigation} checks within the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Lhazaar Principalities]{Lhazaar Principalities}).</p>\n<h3>Captain's Privy and Bath</h3>\n<p>Captain Rockface has her own wash basin, bathtub, and privy.</p>\n<h3>Storage Room</h3>\n<p>The door to the Storage is locked with a superior lock(@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check –4). The storage room has a collect of weapons and the choice pieces of loot she chooses to take from any plunder.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L91WkUzg75E8tVjM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_e26boiu8etj","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"X825Oau4vi3gVWFl","name":"Bilges","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Bilges</h1>\n<p>The lowest deck of the ship, the bilges are a foul, damp place with thick cobwebs above and 1–2 feet of dark, brackish water that stinks abominably below. A ladder leads up to a trap door that opens in the lower hold (area A10), and a single bilge pump rests near the stern. The bilges can also double double as an extension of the ship’s brig if necessary. There are six sets of manacles bolted to the bulkheads.</p>\n<h3>Treasure</h3>\n<p>A number of discarded crates and boxes packed with straw lie in the bilges, among which can be found a suit of leather armor, heavy mace, morning star, cutlass, and 12 sp.</p>\n<p>In addition, a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} check (–1) turns up the following in the dark waters (one item per successful check): a buckler, a masterwork handaxe, a vial of holy water, a tanglefoot bag, two tindertwigs, and 21 gp.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L91WkUzg75E8tVjM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_e26boiu8etj","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"XeRyxVGWh28WoBzG","name":"Theft, Pilfering, and Secrecy","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Theft, Pilfering, and Secrecy</h1>\n<p>To perform any action unobserved on a crowded ship use the following guidelines for modifiers to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} rolls.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li>Attempting a stealthy action in a crowd, such as casting a spell with verbal or somatic components without being noticed: –3 penalty to the roll.</li>\n<li>Attempting a stealthy action where there is a chance of discovery, such as visiting the quartermaster’s store during work, exploring a room during the day, or attempting to open a chest in a room while its occupants are sleeping: –2 penalty to the roll.</li>\n<li>Attempting a stealthy action under cover of a suitable diversion, such as attempting to open lockers when the rest of the crew are working or on deck enjoying themselves: no modifier.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Failure</h3>\n<p>Failing this check means the character attempting the action is merely disturbed and is unable to complete the action. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} on the check, the character is caught red-handed by a random crew member, and might be turned over to @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Roles]{master-at-arms} for discipline.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_f5h8exvluwf","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Ship lore","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"XnKy6uYwlpOoOiu1","name":"Ship Board Actions","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Ship Board Actions</h1>\n<p>In addition to their normal jobs on the ship, the PCs can also utilize their time during the day (and night) to explore the ship, scrounger for gear, interact with their shipmates, or attempt to inf luence NPCs.</p>\n<p>With the PCs potentially scattered across the ship working at their jobs, however, there is a danger that early events in the adventure might focus too much upon the actions of individual characters. Some PCs might have more time on their hands and act accordingly. To avoid this, the PCs’ activities aboard ship—carrying out their assigned tasks; exploring the ship; robbing, bullying, or befriending shipmates; working; or playing—are performed as part of ship actions. These actions reflect the time required to set up or complete an activity, such as gathering enough crew to play a game, scouting out a room to make sure it’s empty, and so on. Remember that even the cook’s mate has a job to do during the day, and ship actions are meant to reflect the available time a PC can carve out from his or her work time without going into too much detail.</p>\n<p>Each hero can normally take two ship actions each day, one during the day and one at night. A hero can also attempt to take up to two additional ship actions during the middle watch in the dead of night (any nighttime ship action marked with an asterisk), but to do so the PC must make a successful @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Vigor} check (–1 for each additional ship action taken) or take a level of  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} for the next day.</p>\n<p>A list of possible ship actions is presented on the following page. As always, use your judgment as to when these actions are appropriate.</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main-heading\">Ship Board Actions</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Daytime Actions</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Work Diligently: </strong>Gain a +1 bonus on any one check for a job's daily task.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Influence: </strong>Make normal checks for a job's daily task and make an attempt to influence a single NPC (skill check based on how it is done).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sneak: </strong>Make normal checks for a job's daily task. Then make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check to avoid detection, followed by a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} to briefly explore one area of the ship.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shop: </strong>Take a –1 penalty on all checks for a job's daily task and visit the quartermaster's store.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shirk:</strong> Take a –1 penalty on all checks for a job's daily task and take time exploring one area of the ship. Make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check to avoid detection, followed by a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} to explore one area of the ship.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Nightime Actions</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sleep: </strong>Go to bed early and sleep through the night (automatically recover one level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Gamble:</strong> Play or gamble on a game of chance.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Entertain:</strong> Make one @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} check to entertain the crew.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Influence:</strong> Attempt to influence a single NPC. (Skill check based on how influencing is done.)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sneak:</strong> Take time exploring one area of the ship. Make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check to avoid detection, followed by a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} (+1) to explore one area of the ship.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Steal: </strong>Attempt to steal something from a locked door or footlocker. The character must make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} roll to avoid being seen as well as a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_ptturwq4bg","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"a5dWjtPnSBr1tjnt","name":"Ship Roles","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Ship Roles</h1>\n<p>All crew members on any ship have specific roles and responsibilities, often with harsh punishments being meted out upon those who shirk their duties. Listed here are some of the standard roles aboard a typical ship. Not all of these roles might be represented on every vessel, but such details can help players understand their characters’ daily duties.</p>\n<h2>Officers</h2>\n<h3>Captain</h3>\n<p>The ultimate authority on any ship responsible for the ship and everything aboard her, his word is law to all on board. The captain chooses where to sail, what are fitting punishments for breeches in discipline,  and who fills the other stations aboard the vessel, among many other command decisions. The captain is the voice of the crew to all beyond the ship. In terms of daily duties, the captain keeps a log of the voyage, manages the affairs of the ship through the officers, working with the navigator to plot courses, and generally serves a four to six hour shift at the helm. Leadership can prove perilous, however, as a captain is, above all, meant to secure success for his ship and crew. Failing to do so increases the threat of mutiny.</p>\n<h3>First Mate</h3>\n<p>The first mate is the number two man on the ship. She is responsible for enforcing the ship’s articles and administering punishment when necessary. The first mate is the trustee of the ship and her crew, often being elected by the crew to the position. She directly represents the crew to the captain. It is her responsibility to serve as a counterbalance to the captain in decisions that might be hazardous to the ship or the crew. A wise captain makes no decisions that his first mate doesn't support. The first mate takes responsibility for prize vessels and picks the treasure that the crew will take from a prize. She is also responsible for counting the booty and splitting the shares according to each crewmembers due. Each day will find her working with her subordinate officers the boatswain, the master gunner, and the master at arms to effectively run the ship. The first mate also serves a turn at the helm, generally a four to six hour shift.</p>\n<h3>Navigator</h3>\n<p>The navigator is responsible for plotting the ship’s course and maintaining that course, thus requiring an strong education and excellent all around seamanship. The navigator maintains all of the ship’s charts and maps as well as the tools of navigation. He is charged with keeping a daily log of every event relating to the sailing of the ship. He records the depth, the currents, the wind patterns, the ship’s location, the locations of reefs and sandbars, and the state of the rigging. He reports directly to the captain. The pilot oversaw the work of the sail-master and almost always has at least one assistant (a pilot’s mate) to help him with his duties. The pilot and his mate both serve separate shifts at the helm in addition to taking readings from the moons and stars to plot and maintain the course.</p>\n<h3>Boatswain</h3>\n<p>The boatswain, or bosun (pronounced “bosun” either way), is responsible for maintaining the ship's seaworthy status. This makes the boatswain accountable for all rope, rigging, anchors, and sails. His duties were to make certain that all the work of running the ship is done. This would also include keeping the watches and maintaining discipline among the deck crew. At the start of the day, the boatswain and those under her weigh anchor, raise the sails and report on the general condition of the ship’s deck to the first mate. The boatswain was often the most feared man on the ship because his obligations often made him uncompromising. It was his responsibility to keep everything “ship-shape”. Day and night, the boatswain drives the crew to do whatever work is required. He maintains the watch log and reports any problems to the first mate.</p>\n<h3>Quartermaster</h3>\n<p>The quartermaster oversees all the supplies and items stored aboard the ship. She maintains the supplies of food, water, sails, rope, wood, and tar, oversees the disbursement of food to the cook, and doles out the rum ration to the crew. The quartermaster also directs the loading of cargo into the hold to maintain the proper ballast to ensure level sailing.</p>\n<h3>Artificer/Mage</h3>\n<p>Many ships that ply the waters around Khorvaire have an artificer and/or mage on board. They can be responsible for the functioning of any magical locomotion of the ship, repairs, general arcane knowledge or any number of other magical needs the ship might have. They are also expected to contribute firepower or counter enemy magical firepower in any ship to ship conflicts that happen on the vessel. </p>\n<h3>Master-at-Arms</h3>\n<p>The Master at Arms is often the most skilled warrior on the crew. He is responsible for training the crew in hand to hand combat. He also leads the ship’s boarding parties and hunting parties when they are necessary. The Master at Arms position is not a separate position on every vessel and often these responsibilities fall to the first mate or quartermaster. When the master at arms position is filled on a ship, he takes orders from and reports to the first mate.</p>\n<h3>Master Gunner</h3>\n<p>The master gunner is in charge of all shipboard artillery, ensuring the weapons are kept in good working order, repaired, and that the crew knows how to use them. She maintains the ballistas, catapults, and so on. The master gunner picks, trains and runs the gunnery crew. He reports to the first mate, but was responsible to the entire ship to make sure the artillery hits the target. He day to day duties consists of drilling the gunnery crew and maintaining the weapons.</p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:1.125em\">Crew</span></h2>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size:1.125em\">Sail-Master</span></h3>\n<p>The Sail-master is the most experienced crewman in the rigging and usually one of the best sailors on the ship. He is responsible for maintaining the sails and the rigging. The Sail-master knows every knot, line, rope, block and tackle in the rigging as well as how to repair them all. He is also responsible for training and running the sail crew as well as overseeing the making and patching of sails. The Sail-master takes orders from and reports to the navigator.</p>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size:1.125em\">Cabin Boy/Girl</span></h3>\n<p>Servant to the captain and other officers, this low-ranking and typically young crew member assists other sailors in their duties and runs various errands across the ship, requiring him or her to gain a measure of understanding of almost all the ship’s roles.</p>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size:1.125em\">Carpenter</span></h3>\n<p>No matter what enchantments or alchemical unguents augment a pirate ship, its heart and bones are still wood. This simple fact makes the carpenter one of the most important positions aboard any vessel. Carpenters are chiefly responsible for maintaining the ship below the deck, finding and plugging leaks, repairing damage, and replacing masts and yards. Carpenters are also responsible for the construction of barrels and crates as necessary to store cargo. The carpenter reports to the boatswain.</p>\n<h3>Cook</h3>\n<p>While the quartermaster normally allocates the rations, the cook and his apprentices make and distribute meals to the crew. Although some better-outfitted vessels employ skilled cooks to attend to the captain and the officers, many cooks are drawn from crew members who have suffered crippling injuries, allowing them to still serve even after such trauma.The cook takes orders from either the quartermaster or the boatswain.</p>\n<h3>Healer</h3>\n<p>Many ships have a healer on board to tend to any injuries that happen. Whether this is a House Jorasco healer, Jorasco trained, or some herbalist with slight training in healing, depends on the vessel. The healer takes orders from the first mate.</p>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size:1.125em\">Rigger</span></h3>\n<p>Riggers work the rigging and unfurl the sails. In battle, next to that of a boarding party, the riggers’ job is one of the most dangerous, as they pull enemy vessels near enough to board. Riggers report to the sail-master and the boatswain.</p>\n<h3>Swab</h3>\n<p>Any sailor who mops the decks. Also used as slang for any low-ranking or unskilled crew member.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_f5h8exvluwf","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Ship lore","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"acDz3n4ZSmht0mKD","name":"Brig","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Brig</h1>\n<p>The main brig is two cells that have enough room to fit two people each if need be, however usually only one creature is held in each cell. At the start of the adventure two of the pirates wake up in one cell. In the other cell is Jakes Magpe awaiting his punishment.</p>\n<p>The manacles in each cell are average locks (–1 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} checks) and the locks on the cell doors are superior locks (–3 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} checks).</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L91WkUzg75E8tVjM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_e26boiu8etj","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"cacdPFb6F3YClNyq","name":"Main Deck","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Main Deck</h1>\n<p>The ship’s main deck runs between the foredeck and poop deck. The mainmast rises from the center of the deck, extending 60 feet into the air and topped by a crow’s nest. Rigging connects the mainmast to the ship’s other masts and can be crossed with DC 10 Acrobatics or Climb checks. Several strands of thick rope are secured to the foot of the mainmast for use as a whipping post. An Escape Artist check (DC 20 + the binder’s CMB) is required to escape the bonds. The ship’s clock, a macabre brass-and copper object depicting worms writhing through whale corpses, hangs from the mast above the whipping post. Not only does the clock keep time, but its bell strikes at dawn and dusk to signal the beginning and the end of the workday.</p>\n<p>Two 10-foot-square hatches sit in the deck fore and aft of the mainmast. These hatches are thick wooden grilles (hardness 5, hp 30, DC 25 Strength check to lift) and open onto the middle hold (area A6) 15 feet below. At the fore of the ship, two doors lead into the officers’ quarters (area A4), while two doors aft lead to the captain’s quarters (area A5). A large wooden box bound in iron sits just beneath the bridge. This sweatbox, used to torment sailors, has just enough room to hold one Medium creature (and can be altered to confine a Small creature). It is locked with a good lock (Disable Device DC 30); Prince Rockface and Mr. Plugg have the keys.</p>\n<p>A small jolly boat (same statistics as a rowboat) sits on the deck next to the port rail. It has two sets of oars but no mast. Although designed to carry four Medium passengers, the jolly boat can fit six at a push.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L91WkUzg75E8tVjM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_e26boiu8etj","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"dDyfNzqrtVqoM86r","name":"The Terror","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">The Terror</h1>\n<p>Ursa Ulm is searching for her father, Noran Nass, a master shipwright. He left under mysterious circumstances several months ago and hasn’t been heard from since. Ursa offers a bounty of $20,000 for her father’s return. The bounty is high because she has heard that it was the Emperor himself who spirited him away. A Streetwise roll at –4 proves she’s correct, and discovers that Noran was one of those “requested” to work on the Terror, the Great Whale’s new battle barge.</p>\n<p>The Terror lies in a deep bay on the island of Terras. It’s protected by two temporary gun emplacements with four guns each. The Terror’s guns can also be manned in an emergency.</p>\n<p>The marines, nine other shipwrights, and 73 workers live in a crudely built circular village on the beach. A dozen marines are always on board the Terror 50 yards offshore, a dozen guard the work details, and a dozen more patrol the island.</p>\n<p>If Noran is rescued, he offers to do a custom renovation on the heroes’ ship, increasing its base Toughness by 2 and its Travel Speed by 1. The others offer individual rewards worth 2d6 x $200.</p>\n<p>Marines (36): Typical Marines (p. 191).</p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_53dtyb3i8lp","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/2. Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"e8jhDVoMZBZ4P6hq","name":"Treasure for the Taking","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Treasure for the Taking</h1>\n<p>“Stumpy” Pete, a regular at the Shipwreck Surprise, has two wooden legs (hence the name). Since being washed up on the island last year he has worked as Azy’s accountant— he’s not much use as a farmer or sailor. The locals suspect he has a hidden stash of treasure somewhere on the island but countless searches have revealed nothing.</p>\n<p>Stumpy approaches the group while they are drinking in the tavern. He invites them to join him for a drink and to partake in a business venture.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“Name’s Stumpy Pete,” he slurs, obviously the worse for drink. “Afore I came to the cay I was a pirate by trade working under a French corsair by the name of Pierre La Grange. He was small fry compared to some—at least until we found treasure.</p>\n<p>“While exploring an island north of the Whips we discovered a stash of treasure buried in a ruined building. We was only a small crew, just the ten of us, but we struck it rich beyond our wildest dreams. Gold, silver, and jewels in abundance just waiting for us to find it.</p>\n<p>“We took what we could carry and left the rest, planning on returning when we could. The captain said carrying too much would make us an easy target if other pirates found out. We spent most of our loot in Baltimus before heading to Shark Bay to acquire a larger ship. Never made it that far though. The ship sank in a storm somewhere off the coast of this island. I was lucky—I was washed up here. Lost my other leg but at least I’m alive.</p>\n<p>“I can tell you doubt my story and I don’t blame you. If you want some proof the treasure exists then look no further.” With that, he removes his right leg and holds it upside down over the table. A small bag slides out and lands with a soft clunk. Stumpy opens the bag to reveal two dozen small diamonds.</p>\n<p>“This is just a taste of what we found. I can’t trust these pirates to help me, but if you’ll take me to the island I’ll share the booty with you— fifty-fifty.”</p>\n</section>\n<p>No one on the island knows Stumpy has the gems—he exchanges them for coin with visiting crews. The treasure is real and the offer genuine. Hard bargaining and a raise on a Persuasion roll can increase the group’s share to 75% of the haul. The only thing “Stumpy” failed to mention was the horrible creature guarding the treasure—another reason he has never returned to the island.</p>\n<p>Stumpy Pete Pete lost his first leg to grapeshot and the second when he was shipwrecked off Azy Cay. He is content with his life on the Cay—he has a steady job, his own shack, and his booty goes further than it would in a big city. All he wants now is the rest of the treasure to see him through in comfort to his dying days. Attributes: Agility d6, Smarts d8, Spirit d8, Strength d6, Vigor d8 Skills: Boating d6, Climbing d8, Fighting d8, Intimidation d6, Notice d6, Swimming d6 Charisma: 0; Pace: 2; Parry: 6; Toughness: 6 Hindrances: Bad Luck, One Leg (twice—suffers –4 penalty to traits requiring mobility and cannot run), Stubborn Edges: Dirty Fighting, Fast Healer, Frugal, Harder to Kill, Rich Gear: Two pistols, crutches, cutlass (Str+d6).</p>\n<h2>Treasure Island</h2>\n<p>The island lies 70 miles due north of Kuwayway and does not appear on any charts—it’s simply too small. Rising steeply from the sea, the cliffs tower 100 feet above the surrounding water. Atop is a rugged plateau covered in dense forest. Aside from a small colony of monkapes and some razor wings the island is uninhabited. Actually that isn’t true—the Sea Hags know about the treasure and sent a guardian to watch over it. (See below for details.)</p>\n<p>Scaling the cliffs requires three Climbing rolls. Failure results in a drop of 1d6 x 5 yards. Stumpy can’t climb and must be winched to the top.</p>\n<p>After getting his bearings, Stumpy leads the group north through the forest. The short walk to the ruin involves crossing rugged ground and hacking through the forest—not to mention having to walk at Stumpy’s slow pace. Have everyone make Vigor rolls. A failure results in a level of Fatigue, recovered after 15 minutes rest.</p>\n<p>The ruin once served as a Kieran noble’s hunting retreat but fell into disuse after the Flood. The owner and servants are all dead— drowned in an attempt to cross the Flotsam Sea and reach the “safety” of Kiera. Thick vines cling to the walls and only the main entrance shows any sign of disturbance—this is where “Stumpy” and his crew entered last year.</p>\n<p>The treasure belonged to a pirate (now resting at the bottom of sea) who found the island several years ago and thought it a safe place to conceal his loot.</p>\n<p>Have the characters make Notice rolls. On a success, they realize Stumpy has grown very nervous, wringing his hands and glancing quickly from side to side. If questioned he says, “Strange being back that’s all. Reminds me of my dead shipmates. Come on, the loot’s in the ballroom. Let’s get it and go.”</p>\n<p>Stumpy leads the group to the ballroom and points to some flagstones in the far corner. The stones lift easily to reveal six chests, each full to bursting with treasure. Disturbing the chests alerts the Sea Hags’ guardian lurking in the forest nearby. It attacks as the group leaves the ruin.</p>\n<p> Guardian Beast: The guardian beast is actually a giant zombie monkape, placed here by the Sea Hags to guard the treasure. Use the statistics for a regular giant monkape (p. 192) but add the Fear, Fearless, and Undead Special Ability (as per a zombie). The beast concentrates its attacks on the character carrying the mummified head.</p>\n<p> Booty: Two King’s Ransoms. In addition there is a golden triangle engraved with strange writing and a wooden box containing a mummified head.</p>\n<h2>Mummified Head</h2>\n<p>The head is the true reason the Sea Hags sent a guardian to the island. It belonged to a powerful archmage who sacrificed his life to give the inhabitants of Caribdus a chance to defeat the three sisters. The head is alive—sort of—and can still use its magic. When the lid is lifted the eyes open and a disembodied voices speaks to the heroes, “My magic is yours to command but only against the three sisters.”</p>\n<p>It has 50 Power Points, a d12+2 Spellcasting, and knows every spell, but can only cast them in the final battles against the Sea Hags. Power Points are not recharged—once the last one is spent the head crumbles to dust.</p>\n<p>Neither the Hags nor their minions can touch the head or affect it with magic—hence the zombie monkape guardian.</p>\n<p>If the group has already defeated the Sea Hags the head is less powerful—it can teach a mage a single spell, ignoring the usual rank requirement. This takes 2d6 hours of instruction, after which the mage may add to spell to his repertoire. The head then crumbles to dust.</p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_53dtyb3i8lp","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/2. Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"eltDYUweV0xcQduQ","name":"Risky Games in the Bilges","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Risky Games in the Bilges</h1>\n<p> </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_5m4g64zt3jr","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/3. Aboard the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"fOqtQyLwwf8hbwG5","name":"Pirates of Cyre Characters","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Pirates of Cyre Characters</h1>\n<h2>Cyre is Destroyed!</h2>\n<p>Cyre is Destroyed! Gone! No one would help us after the Mournland rolled through. We were even forgotten from the negotiating table at the laughable Treaty of Thronehold. As well intended as Prince Oargev might be, New Cyre is on Brelish land. There no telling when the \"generosity\" of that throne (or the Parliment) will want their land back. There is little hope that the Mournland can be reversed. Even if it could, there is not enough Cyrans left to stop the rush of Karrns, Thranes, and Brelanders that would come in to take the land. </p>\n<p>If Cyre is to survive, you need to take matters into your own hands. You have lived your life on the sea for Cyre, so it's time to take what you know and see how you can support Cyre. Since nobody seems to care about Cyrans, maybe it is time to take what we can to give to those Cyrans who now have nothing. So now it is time to turn to piracy to help out the Cryans that survive. The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Lhazaar Principalities]{Lhazaar Principalities} are too chaotic and disjointed now with the largest shipping lanes in Khorvaire after the loss of the Great Canal. It is time to take some of the wealth from those that have so much to help those that have lost so much. Who knows, with a kind eye from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Arawai]{Arawai}, and a blessing from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Devourer]{the Devourer}, maybe you might acquire enough plunder and noteriety (or Infamy) to be able to claim some land or even a prinipality for the survivors of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Cyre]{Cyre}. </p>\n<h2>Campaign Intention</h2>\n<p>In the Pirates of Cyre campaign, you are going to take on the role of Cyrans who survived the Day of Mourning or those friendly and sympathetic to the Cyran plight. Fed up with how Cyrans are being treated by the other nations, you are choosing to use your life long knowledge of the sea, to turn to piracy.</p>\n<p>This campaign is intended to be a very pulpy and swashbuckling in nature. It will start off on some rails, but will open up into a large sand box that will be very much driven by you.</p>\n<p>Your reasons for turning to piracy could include any number of reasons. Here are some examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Prince Oargev, or someone who has his ear, has asked or planted a seed in you to use your skills in this manner to find a new home for Cyrans or at least send money to support New Cyre.</li>\n<li>Perhaps you fear that Breland will eventually kick Cyrans out of New Cyre and leave everyone you know and love left, once again homeless. You can change that.</li>\n<li>You are just plain bitter at any number of the other nations for what they did to Cyre. Either for unjustly starting the new war, what you see as war crimes during the war, shutting their doors to your people in thier time of greatest need, or something else. Regardless, you are only giving them what they deserve.</li>\n<li>You don't trust Prince Oargev to do right by Cyrans. He is too beholden to Breland, so you will take matters into your own hands to help yourselves, and any other Cyrans that can see what you are doing.</li>\n<li>You survived the Day of Mourning by being at sea, and have been here in the Lhazaar for a long time now. The law here is that you keep what you take. This has just finally started to rub off. Why not do this for Cyrans?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Regardless of your reasons, the most important thing to keep in mind when creating your character is that piracy plays a significant role in this campaign, and your character should be willing on some level to engage in it. Whether you are pirates with or without honor makes no difference. It also does not matter if you are just interested in plundering wealth just for self or for other Cyrans, raiding, overthrowing an existing prince, or finding land for a new home for Cyre. All these options have a place in this campaign, and you get to decide what that is. Outside of there being piracy, there is no intention to force you players into being a certian kind of pirate.</p>\n<p> </p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":4},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_sfbrzx24rkb","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Player Character Guide","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"fitTepd1kSfxudlF","name":"05 Wrecked on Bonewreck Isle","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Wrecked on Bonewreck Isle</h1>\n<p>The two most likely places to land on @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Bonewreck Isle]{Bonewreck Isle} are near an abandoned fishing village on the northern shore or the beach to the east of the isle.</p>\n<h3>Through the Swamp</h3>\n<p>If the swabs land in the fishing village and then head through the Swamp they will encounter the Mire. This a place where a salt river oozes through the swamp forming a barrier of quicksand and marsh. Though the trees provide a means to cross the The renants of an old wooden bridge remain across the bog.</p>\n<p>Crossing this area is a dramatic task requiring 4 successes in 3 rounds per character. To complicate things gaint frogs will come out of the mud in round two trying to snatch some easy food.</p>\n<h3>Whores Boudoir</h3>\n<p>A terrible stench fills the swamp here, a fetid odor of cheap perfume and rotting flesh. A huge tree stands in the middle of a clearing in the swamp, draped with some sort of huge tent. Lurid, painted faces cover both the tree trunk and tent, and both are decorated with rotting humanoid body parts and carpets of squirming insects.</p>\n<p>This is the home of the three ghouls that have survived from the wreck of the <em>Infernus. </em>This is the remnants of a considerable tent that is lashed around a great tree. Clouds of flies dance around all the decay.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Ghoul]{Ghoul} (3)</li>\n</ul>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/ambience/nautical/tropical-island-shoreline-02.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_0gxlbqom8dl","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/1. Mourners of Lhazaar Plot Point","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"hbaGKXYQjJRQeodm","name":"#[CF_tempEntity]","content":"","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_5m4g64zt3jr","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/3. Aboard the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000","name":"3. Aboard the Storm Reaver","children":["Sc8zngwHZvU5mmmY","0her9fqDEQGD0sd0","s9fyLkRMd21SgmaD","eltDYUweV0xcQduQ","8579PWn4dLL6v9kV","rOIFr1FLjz0CznqP","j8zYeeugTzUe2HdO"],"folderPath":["temp_bmn52t4oyo"]}}}
{"_id":"j8zYeeugTzUe2HdO","name":"Trouble in the Sun","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Trouble in the Sun</h1>\n<p>Approaching the Slithering Coast, the waters become shallow and navigation is tricky. As the afternoon wears on, Mr. Lagraa calls the swabs together on the main deck, plus one crew memeber friendly to them. At his feet lie four crab pots. Lagraa informs the swabs that the captain wants fresh crab for supper. Lagraa points to a reef lying some 200 feet north of the ship and instructs them to swim to the reef, fill the pots with crabs, and swim back. Lagraa brooks no further discussion.</p>\n<p>The waters are calm and clear (visibility 100 feet). The initial swim (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} checks) across the open water passes without event, and they soon approach a superb coral reef, measuring approximately 100 yards square, lying between 5 and 30 feet below the surface. Many crabs inhabit the reef. Filling up the crab pots is a modified @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dramatic Tasks]{Dramatic Task}. The dramatic task has four rounds, each success token is a crab into one of the crab pots. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival} checks can be made every round. Alternately @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} checks (–2) can be made one round and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} checks can be made another round.</p>\n<p><strong>Creatures:</strong> Two reefclaws lair in the reef. They swim out during the 3rd round of the dramatic task. They can be fended off with an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} check (–1), or they can be attacked and killed with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} checks (–3). Fending off the reefclaws does not fill a crab pot with success tokens, failure to fend off or kill the reefclaws results in a level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} each round from each of the reefclaws. Failure on checks to fend off or kill them results in a Wound.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Reefclaw]{Reefclaw} (2)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Treasure:</strong> Reefclaws make very good eating, and a single reefclaw fills a crab pot. If the swabs bring back any reefclaws for the captain’s supper, the captain rewards them by returning all of one swab’s equipment.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_5m4g64zt3jr","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/3. Aboard the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"jFJFL5sly5U5OGOF","name":"06 Rescue in Riptide Cove","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Rescue in Riptide Cove</h1>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_0gxlbqom8dl","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/1. Mourners of Lhazaar Plot Point","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"jaCfiP0NV7KRc1K9","name":"Poop Deck","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Poop Deck</h1>\n<p>This raised deck stands 10 feet above the quarter deck and 25 feet above the main deck. The mizzenmast rises 30 feet above this deck. There are a couple of balista's that are stored on this deck.</p>\n<p><span style=\"color:#3598db\">Prince Rockface</span> and <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Mr. Lagraa</span> spend most of their time on the poop deck. When the captain is on deck, the quarter deck and poop castle are off-limits to everyone but officers.</p>\n<p>An iron cage hangs from the side of the mizzenmast, containing the body of <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Harmak Gruft</span>, a pirate who beat the captain at dice. Gruft is dead, but his ugly parrot <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Pluck </span>perches atop the cage, still waiting for its master to awaken. The aptly named <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Pluck</span>, which has lost more than few of its feathers, could make a good pet or familiar if it can be lured down (such as with magic, a successful wild empathy check, or an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Animal Handling]{Animal Handling} check (–1)). <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Pluck </span>is considered unfriendly and possesses a considerable vocabulary of appalling curse words.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L91WkUzg75E8tVjM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_e26boiu8etj","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"k0auIA2dwIxShmV3","name":"Mister Lagraa","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<p>Mister Lagraa is an angry young woman. He’s always furious about something, but somehow her rage simmers like a stew, and even when she loses her temper she quickly seems to gain control again. A sadist and bully, Lagraa has had a hard, desperate life—few places are more dangerous to grow up than the dockside streets of the Shackles. Only 21 years of age, the memories and scars of Lagraa’s formative years are very fresh, and now she intends to have her revenge.</p>\n<p>Lagraa is also incredibly ambitious—he intends to captain her own ship someday, and she joined the crew of the <em>Storm Reaver</em> purely for her own ends. Thanks to her ruthless devotion to Prince Rockface’s orders, her rise has been meteoric. In just 11 months aboard the <em>Storm Reaver</em>, she has wormed, blackmailed, and murdered her way to the position of first mate, in truth a job well beyond her abilities. she masks her own inadequacies by pointing out those of others.</p>\n<p>Everyone on board the <em>Storm Reaver</em> knows that the first mate is the captain’s right hand when it comes to dealing with the ship’s crew, but Prince Rockface’s other officers form a close inner circle that Lagraa can’t seem to penetrate, a fact that vexes him to no end. Nevertheless, Prince Rockface is sure to punish anyone who attacks Mr. Lagraa, a fact that every member of the crew is acutely aware of.</p>\n<p>To Mister Lagraa, honor, friendship, and teamwork are alien concepts. she believes that discipline is the only thing that matters at sea, and that the constant threat of ruthless punishment is the only thing that can keep a crew of cutthroats and scoundrels in line. she strikes first, and asks questions later. Lagraa is not a forgiving woman, and if someone does get the better of him, Lagraa takes time to plot her revenge in the cruelest way she can think of.</p>\n<p>Bald except for a black ponytail and sporting long, narrow beard, Mister Lagraa somehow looks angry, miserable, and uncomfortable, all at the same time. Bare-chested, she wears an immaculate coat with pearl buttons and carries a cat-o’-nine-tails with him at all times. she clearly takes great pride in himself—everything about him shines, from the polish on her boots to the dome of her head. her teeth are gray and yellow, however, and her face is fixed in an almost constant grimace.</p>\n<h2>Gossip</h2>\n<p>The PCs can learn the following about Mister Lagraa with successful Diplomacy checks to gather information.</p>\n<p>DC 5: If Scourge is a bastard, then Mister Lagraa is her mother and father. One piece of advice—do as she says.</p>\n<p>DC 10: First mate? He’s barely been on board a year! The apple of the captain’s eye, that one. Prince Rockface treats him like a son—but not a legitimate one, of course.</p>\n<p>DC 15: That cutlass of her is magical, see, no doubt about that, and she wields that cat like it was her own arm. I’ve seen him using both in combat. Despite her pettish looks, he’s some fighter by all accounts.</p>\n<p>DC 20: People who cross Lagraa end up dead—stabbed, poisoned, throttled, thrown overboard. Take your pick, they always end up dead. she has friends everywhere, high and low.</p>\n<h2>CampaiGn Role</h2>\n<p>Mister Lagraa (and to a similar extent her repulsive sidekick Master Scourge) presents a challenge for you as GM. she is the main villain of the adventure, yet at the beginning she has considerable inf luence and is practically unassailable. The challenge is to make the PCs loathe him without pushing them to openly attack him, an act that results in keelhauling.</p>\n<p>The penalty for murder on the <em>Storm Reaver</em> should be enough to keep a lid on your player’s desires, but be careful not to overuse her bullying. Lagraa oversees the punishments for infractions on the ship, and does so with relish, but it is Master Scourge, her toadying subordinate, who actually carries out most of the disciplining and poisons the first mate’s mind against the PCs. Again, be careful not to overplay the bullying and sadism, but make sure it is prevalent. With care, you can develop a brooding hatred in your players for this nasty piece of work, and they’ll relish their final encounter with him when the chance eventually presents itself.</p>\n<p>If your players are more unequivocal, however, and likely to bring things to a head before leaving the <em>Storm Reaver</em>, you should bluntly remind them of the consequences of murder. If the keelhauling of Jakes Magpie on the first night aboard the ship doesn’t do the trick, you can have an NPC whom the PCs are growing close to kill someone early on in the adventure, and be keelhauled as punishment.</p>\n<p>Mister Lagraa’s burning ambition leads him to make a return later in the Adventure Path should she somehow survive this adventure. At the table, adventures often take a step away from the predicted plot, and “The <em>Storm Reaver</em> Mutiny” is no exception. The PCs’ mutiny aboard the Man’s Promise may transpire earlier than is written, or circumstances might dictate that Lagraa and some of her cronies somehow escape. Lagraa is certain to brood upon her lost influence, while avoiding her former captain at all costs. Prince Rockface is certain to be unforgiving if she finds that Lagraa has lost the Man’s Promise and yet still lives. Lagraa limps away and broods on her failure, slowly whispering words to the powerful and great as she plots her revenge. she can appear again as an accomplice of one of the more powerful pirate lords or as a Free Captain in her own right, with a handpicked crew of cutthroats and a dozen disciplinary officers aboard her new ship, the Severe.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"monks-enhanced-journal":{"type":"base","_viewcount":2,"role":"FIrst Mate","location":"The Wormwood","race":"Orc","gender":"","age":"21","eyes":"Green","skin":"","hair":"Black","profession":"","voice":"","faction":"","height":"","weight":"","traits":"","ideals":"","bonds":"","flaws":"","longterm":"","shortterm":"","beliefs":"","secret":"","DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":{"notes":""},"scrollPos":"{\".description\":50}"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_wu5utkhw5ta","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Crew of the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"l1ninIZtPqDvOX4a","name":"Thieves in the Night","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Thieves in the Night</h1>\n<p>One night while sitting at the Red Lantern, the heroes are watched by a man named Kimyun Lee, a Korean from Earth, circa 1750. If one of the player characters seems a shady, sneaky sort, Kimyun approaches with a strange offer.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“You do not know me, but I am a businessman here in Deiking. I have been hired by certain parties to find a person of unparalleled skills in stealth and intrusion. Might you know such a person?”</p>\n</section>\n<p>If the character says yes, or points out another of his crew, Kimyun proceeds.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“There is a junk at the harbor called the King of Siam. I am looking for someone to sneak aboard the ship, locate its bell, steal it, and replace it with a duplicate. All without alerting the crew.</p>\n<p>If you are successful, drop the bell in the rain barrel around back of this very establishment by first light. If it is there in the morning, I will meet you for dinner and pay you your reward. If the crew detects your presence, even if you bring me the bell, I will pay each of you 50 pieces of eight. If you manage it without detection, I will pay you 200 pieces of eight each.”</p>\n</section>\n<p>If Kimyun is questioned about the importance of the bell, he says that it is magical but will not say what powers it possesses. This and the task itself are all a test to see if the crew can be trusted. In fact, the King of Siam is Kimyun’s own ship! Kimyun can offer them a longboat to reach the King if they don’t have one of their own.</p>\n<h3>The King of Siam</h3>\n<p>The Siam is anchored a few hundred yards offshore. It’s a typical junk with a skeleton crew of 15, five of whom are on watch at any given time. The rest are likely gambling and drinking in the hold until they pass out or go to sleep, sometime around the witching hour.</p>\n<p>One man sits on each side, and the fifth lurks in the crow’s nest. The sailors aren’t expecting an intrusion, but are fairly watchful. Use the normal rules for Stealth, and be sure to give the characters bonuses for the darkness (+2) and medium cover (+2). If the sailors spot the thieves, they attack.</p>\n<p>Use typical Sailor statistics for the crew (page 199). Those on watch are armed with muskets and short swords.</p>\n<p>The ship’s bell is located under the main mast. If a character doesn’t specifically indicate he’s muffling the knocker somehow, the bell makes a light sound and three of the five guards get a Notice roll to hear it. If they do, they investigate. The same goes for hanging the replacement bell. Hearing the bell doesn’t mean the heroes are detected, however. The guards must actually see the thieves for them to “fail” in this regard.  Sailors (15): p. 199.</p>\n<h2>Completion</h2>\n<p>If the heroes are successful in retrieving the bell without being seen, Kimyun meets them as promised over dinner the next day. He first pays them their reward—under the table—then whispers the following.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“The bell is not magical. This was merely a test to see if you had the skills to retrieve it, and the trustworthiness to bring it to me. If you are interested in a more dangerous but much more lucrative job, meet me at Tonkan Point tonight at midnight. Come prepared for a similar mission.”</p>\n<p>Tonkan Point is a rocky outcropping a mile south of the main harbor. Kimyun and seven mercenaries are waiting there with his longboat. In the boat is a barrel with bright golden bands.</p>\n<p>“A ship in the harbor was loaded with supplies bound for Kiera today. In its hold are a dozen casks of the purest opium. One of them bears golden bands just like the one in the longboat. I want this barrel in its place.</p>\n<p>The pay is 10,000 pieces of eight. If you accept, I will tell you the name of the ship and you can be on your way. We’ll wait here with your payment.”</p>\n</section>\n<p>If the group agrees, Kimyun continues.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“The ship is the Pan Lung. It normally has a crew of 40, but tonight most are carousing in Deiking and will not be back until morning. Those who remain are well-paid and quite competent, I can assure you.</p>\n<p>There are 18 men aboard the ship. Half will be awake and on duty at any given time. They are commanded by a veteran mercenary named Kang. If they catch you, they will torture you to find out who hired you, then kill you. As you might guess, my name is not really Kimyun, so I have little to fear if you fail other than I will try my plan another day.”</p>\n</section>\n<p>Kimyun has been hired by Kieran rebels to “spike” the Emperor’s opium, hopefully killing him or at least driving him so mad even his own advisors will be forced to put him down. The barrel contains opium laced with other poisons that should do the trick. The cask marked in gold trim is the purest blend, a special present to the Mad Emperor from the Deiking warlords.</p>\n<h2>The Pan Lung</h2>\n<p>This is another typical junk, surprisingly similar to the King of Siam. This time however, two guards sit on each side, and one stands in the crow’s nest. Kang frequently wanders the decks as well. It may be difficult for the heroes to slip into the hold undetected, but this time they can use a distraction if they want. It’s okay if Kang and his guards know they’ve been raided—as long as they don’t realize the Emperor’s opium has been spiked.</p>\n<p>How your group manages to pull off this monumental feat is up to them, of course.</p>\n<p> Guards (18): The 18 crew are Veteran Pirates (p. 195). Kang is a Pirate Captain.</p>\n<h2>Failure</h2>\n<p>If they are discovered, Kang does indeed bind and torture them for all they know. The captain of the ship, Minh Dhai, returns a few hours after first light with some of the crew. He sits in on the torture, makes a report for the warlords, and then waits in harbor for a day for their reply. Most likely, the heroes either spill their guts or die in the process (see below). Once Dhai has all the information he feels he can glean from the prisoners, he sends them to the prison for a public beheading. This occurs 1d4 days later and is a good time to give your heroes a chance to escape.</p>\n<p>Withstanding Kang’s gruesome torture techniques is a Spirit roll at –6 each day. Those who fail tell him everything he wants to know. Clever lies reduce the penalty to –4.</p>\n<h2>Success</h2>\n<p>If the cask is successfully replaced, Kimyun greets them on the shore and pays them the ransom as promised—though he demands they leave Deiking immediately and not return for many months. He’s not above a double-cross if they’ve angered him in some way, but mostly he wants them paid and off the island.</p>\n<p> Kimyun and Guards (50): Use typical Veteran Pirate stats for the mercenaries (p. 195). Treat Kimyun as a Pirate Captain.</p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_53dtyb3i8lp","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/2. Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"lYmS2D1Vbo3EtnYW","name":"The Dragonshard Ship","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">The Dragonshard Ship</h1>\n<p>Mas Mako, a heavily-scarred masaquani pirate captain, offers the heroes a chance to take part in a daring act of piracy. He has learned that a Kieran frigate loaded with iron is arriving in Baltimus in three weeks. If the group is willing to join forces he agrees to split the cargo fifty-fifty. Mas owns the brigantine Daughter of Thunder.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately for Mas, he didn’t learn the privateer galleons Hound and Venture Folly were escorting the frigate. Whether or not the heroes decide to carry on with the attack once they see the galleons is up to them—Mas goes it alone if they chicken out.</p>\n<p>If Mas takes on all three ships alone he is captured. Hoping to save his neck from the noose he tells the privateers the player characters were the ringleaders and insists he was forced to take part in the raid. He still hangs for his crime but the privateers come looking for their new enemies.</p>\n<p>The frigate has a crew of twelve—a Wild Card Sailor captain and 11 regular Sailors. The galleons each have a Wild Card Veteran Privateer captain and a crew of 50 Privateers.</p>\n<p> Mas’s Pirates (31): 30 Typical Pirates and Mas Mako, a Wild Card Pirate Captain (p. 195).</p>\n<p> Booty: Ten cargo spaces of iron and any captured vessels split equally between the group and Mas.</p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_53dtyb3i8lp","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/2. Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
