{"_id":"uBLRsS3lJKLrI2XW","name":"Grog Ration","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Grog Ration</h1>\n<p>Sailors require significant quanitities of fresh water on extended sea voyages. Though fresh water was taken aboard in casks, they can often quickly develope algae and become slimy. This water became mixed with some sort of distilled spirits to make it palatable. </p>\n<p>Aboard many ships, half a pint of grog is distributed to each crew member at dusk. The grog is made from some form of distilled spirits, most often brandy, mead, rum, or whiskey. The grog is staggeringly strong, and is often watered down, making it grog. The grog ration is doled out more to keep the crew sated and docile than for recreation, which is why it is doled out in the evening after a long day of work.</p>\n<p>The penalty for selling or spilling the ration is @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Punishments]{six lashes}, or @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Punishments]{six lashes} from a cat-o’-nine-tails for a second offense. Deliberately tipping away rum on board a crowded ship without being seen requires a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check.</p>\n<p>While on merchant or navy vessels grog rations are strictly limited, on pirate ships, crew members can often request more grog if they please.</p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_ptturwq4bg","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"uLXIslJKJfq5RcQO","name":"Crew Entertainment","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Crew Entertainment</h1>\n<p>With time on their hands and precious few places to go, sailors and pirates have come up with an astonishing array of pastimes.</p>\n<h3>Songs and Stories</h3>\n<p>One way sailors amuse themselves is through songs and stories. Sailors love a good sea chantey, and characters with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} quickly find themselves popular members of the crew. If a character succeeds at a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} check, he gains a +1 bonus per @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} to social checks made to interact with any listener among the crew for the next 24 hours, up to a maximum of +4. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure}, however, indicates that the next time he attempts to use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} to entertain the crew, everyone ignores him.</p>\n<h3>Gambling Games</h3>\n<p>Other recreations have two things in common: they are dangerous, and they are played for money. When betting on any of the following games, the minimum bet is 1 gp, and the maximum ready cash any sailor in the lesser crew is likely to have is 20 gp. Some people are bad losers—the ramifications of this are left for the GM to decide.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Arm Wrestling:</strong> Not merely typical arm wrestling bouts, such matches are usually conducted on a barrel top covered in broken glass, knives, or caltrops. Participants make opposed @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength} checks, with the higher result determining the winner, and the loser taking an level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises} as his hand and arm are pushed onto whatever lies on the table.</li>\n<li><strong>Hog Lob: </strong>Participants lob a lead ingot covered in a greased piglet skin, the “hog,” as far across the deck as possible. This game is resolved by @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} checks between any number of players, who agree on a bet beforehand. The hog counts as an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Improvised Weapons]{improvised weapon}. Some pirates claim to have participated in games played against Devourer using a live hog.</li>\n<li><strong>Heave:</strong> This potentially deadly drinking game is played with rum and takes place between any number of pirates, who bet to predict the winner beforehand. Each pirate drinks a half pint of rum in one swig. Doing so forces participants to make a successful @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Vigor} check –1 or take a level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}. This check increases by –1 for each consecutive drink. Pirates then take turns drinking until only one is left standing. Some tales tell of entire crews drinking themselves to death through this game, leaving ships of drunk ghosts wandering the shipping routes.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_f5h8exvluwf","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Ship lore","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"uMiAoyZLIMEFFICD","name":"Debauchery","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Debauchery</h1>\n<p>Mannie Morkan is a proud citizen of Ograpog who despises the Baltimus’ family for deserting King Amemnus in his hour of need. He has said so in public many times—enough so that Bruno Baltimus secretly invited Morkan’s daughter to one of his after-hours parties. The starstruck 17-year old girl foolishly accepted the invitation. The next morning, Morrie was left dazed and abused on Morkan’s doorstep. The message was clear.</p>\n<h3>Morkan’s Revenge</h3>\n<p>Morkan pretended to back down, but in truth his anger seethes like a boiling teapot. The merchant now seeks an assassin—one with the stomach to slaughter Bruno and his entire group of rakes as they defile themselves at one of their midnight soirées.</p>\n<p>How Morkan learns of the player characters is up to you. They must be of a somewhat tarnished disposition and quite capable to be approached by the mad father. They must also be somewhat charming, for Morkan’s plan is for them to gain Bruno Baltimus’ trust and then betray him.</p>\n<p>When Mannie is finally ready to make his offer, he approaches the crew and drops a piece of paper in their hands. On the paper is a single word— Versalis. A Common Knowledge roll at –2 (–4 to visitors) allows a hero to remember this as a legendary masaquani sword, equivalent to Earth’s Excalibur.</p>\n<p>Assuming the party follows Morkan outside, he says the following:</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“I’m looking for agents of vengeance. Men and women who aren’t afraid to get their hands dirty. Very dirty. I’m looking for curs who can pretend to be a man’s best friend and then gut him from behind when he turns his back. If I can find such hirelings, and if they avenge my family, I will pass on a treasure unlike any they have ever seen.”</p>\n</section>\n<p>Morkan is taking a bit of a risk here—the crew could simply beat him until he revealed the location of Versalis. His daughter, Morrie, watches from a dark corner beyond, but can do little but scream if the crew attempts to attack her father. Even this is a risk because the sailors could reveal what Mannie said to Baltimus, which would almost certainly result in his and his daughter’s death.</p>\n<p>Mannie is desperate now though. He’s sick and knows he won’t live much longer. His daughter cannot wield Versalis, and he has no other living kin to give it to, so this is his final gift to his family. It’s all or nothing.</p>\n<h3>The Mark</h3>\n<p>If the heroes agree to Mannie’s offer, he bows his head, grits his teeth, and says: “Do you know who Bruno Baltimus is?” That should be enough to make most characters think twice about this assignment. Bruno Baltimus is the son of Byron Baltimus, the founder of the city and one of the founders of the Great Harbor system itself. If the group seems undaunted, however, Mannie continues:</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“What the father did to the King of Ograpog was treason. What he did to this city makes my skin crawl. What his son and his rakes did to my daughter makes my blood boil.</p>\n<p>I have forged invitations to Bruno’s next gala in three days. I want you to go to the party and find a way to make him invite you to his after hours debauchery. The one he throws after the other guests leave. While he and his friends defile themselves, I want you to strike. Kill them all. I don’t care if they suffer or not, I just want them dead, dead, DEAD!”</p>\n</section>\n<p>Mannie is visibly shaking by this point. Spit flies from his lips and his skin turns red as a beet. If the crew agrees, Morkan hands over a blank invitation for one person and his “entourage.” The party is to be held three nights from tonight.</p>\n<h3>Baltimus Manor</h3>\n<p>The Manor is a huge marble building on the high cliffs of Baltimus. The gala begins with a feast around dinner time (6 bells) and continues until 11 bells or so. At that point the doors are closed and the staff begins to clean.</p>\n<p>Bruno and a dozen of his closest friends plus twice that number of young women head into the heir’s parlor upstairs, a maze of thin, oriental-style partitions hiding numerous beds, hookahs, liquor, and erotic paintings. A trio of musicians even plays soft and suggestive music from behind one of the walls.</p>\n<p>Getting invited to this soiree requires some serious roleplaying as well as a few key Persuasion rolls. Fellow hunters, nobles, and playboys fit well with Bruno and his band, as do attractive women.</p>\n<p>The activities start with wine and dancing and quickly descend into depravity from there.</p>\n<p>If the player characters are part of the debauchery, they can simply grab their weapons and do as they will. The exterior walls of the room are quite thick, so even gunshots aren’t likely to rouse the estate’s guards as long as the doors remain shut and the large window overhead remains intact.</p>\n<p>Bruno tries to fight at first, but as soon as he realizes he’s outnumbered he rallies behind some of his surviving rakes, then suddenly abandons them and leaps for the staircase yelling “Guards!” A dozen guards arrive wherever Bruno is 1d6 rounds after they hear his yell.</p>\n<p>If the assassins weren’t invited to the party, they’ll need to break in somehow, perhaps posing as servants or simply sneaking through the house somehow.</p>\n<p>Bruno has five guards posted inside the house, and another dozen circle the grounds outside.</p>\n<p>Guards (17): Use veteran City Watch (p. 184) for the 17 guards stationed around the manor.</p>\n<p>Rakes (13): Bruno and his twelve friends are athletic outdoorsmen. Use City Watch statistics (p. 184) for the lecherous nobles. Bruno is a Wild Card.</p>\n<p>Booty: The heroes have just enough time to gather a King’s Ransom.</p>\n<h3>Aftermath</h3>\n<p>What happens next depends on the assassins’ actions. The British East India Company puts out a $10,000 bounty on the killers. Everywhere the group goes, they are hunted and hounded. Even after they leave Baltimus, they are likely to be found as news of the deed spreads around Caribdus. Both good souls and greedy ones partake in the chase, hoping to bring these foul killers to justice—and collect the reward.</p>\n<p>Byron’s Diary: If the heroes are here to find Byron’s diary, they do so after slaying Bruno. If they try to talk him into giving them his father’s records, he agrees if convinced that it will save the world (a Persuasion roll at –2).</p>\n<p>Versalis: Mannie Morkan lives up to his promise. He meets the group at their preappointed spot and gives them Versalis, one of the most powerful swords in Caribdus.</p>\n<p>Versalis: Anytime the wielder of Versalis hits with a raise, the foe must make a Vigor roll at –2 or be beheaded and die instantly. The magic works on any living creature of Size –2 to +2 that has a discernible head.</p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_53dtyb3i8lp","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/2. Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"v4w8i8JJjzYB75fO","name":"Workshop","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Workshop</h1>\n<p>This cramped room is shared by @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Grovus Stormbread]{Grovus Stormbread} and @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Hakrilli Quarne]{Hakrilli Quarne}. This room is obviously an arcane workshop chalk full of over stuffed book shelves, a couple work benches, and a table in the center of the room. Ever available space is filled with equipment, tools, and unfinished experiments. There are numerous curiosities and unsettling objects in here that either <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Grovus </span>or <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Hakrilli </span>are studying.</p>\n<p>There are any numerous potions, scrolls, and minor magical items that can be found here. With the disorder that is present here it is more likely to steal something here that will go unnoticed. If one can get past the good lock on the door and the trapped handle.</p>\n<h2 class=\"trap\">Shocking Trap</h2>\n<p><strong>Type:</strong> Magical; <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} Check:</strong> Yes, at –2; <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} Check:</strong> Yes, at –3</p>\n<p><strong>Trigger:</strong> If someone who tries to open the door does not speak <span style=\"color:#e67e23\">\"Devourer protect us\"</span>, will active the trap.</p>\n<p><strong>Effect:</strong> The door handle triggers an electrical shock dealing ([[/r 2d6x=]] damage).</p>\n<p> </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L91WkUzg75E8tVjM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_e26boiu8etj","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"vmlCjdWCyrYJxvxn","name":"Crew of the Storm Reaver","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Crew of the Storm Reaver</h1>\n<h2>Swabs</h2>\n<h3>Sandara Quinn</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Female human, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> swab, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> helpful<br />Cleric of Arawai, only firm ally the party will have from the start.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}</p>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size:1.125em\">Giffer Tibbs</span></h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Male dwarf, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> swab, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> neutral<br />A bedraggled dwarf with one eye.</p>\n<h3>Rosie Cusswell</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Female dwarf, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> swab, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> neutral<br />Short even for a dwarf, Rosie Cusswell is fierce and has more muscles than most of the crew. She also has a fouler mouth than all the crew put together. Rosie is from Cliffscrape, and like the characters was impressed onto the <em>Storm Reaver's</em> crew. She has been on the ship for over a week and has already made her mark threatening others who mess with her. She has a healthy hatred of Mr. Dabrak and Scourge. She loves food, drink, and tall tales. Anyone who provides her with any of those gains a +1 bonus to any check to influence her. She is missing her fiddle, and has been unable to convince Grok to give it back to her. Any character that can recover her fiddle for her, will immediately made a firm friend of Rosie.</p>\n<h3>Tamroth Scrimshaw</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Female orc, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> swab, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> neutral<br />Young lass that is talented in carving scrimshaw.</p>\n<h3>\"Badger\" Stonehurler</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Male dwarf, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> swab, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> uncooperative<br />An old dwarf who has his gray hear shaved into strips.</p>\n<h3>Tilly Tordanthan</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Female dwarf, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> swab, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> uncooperative<br />A tough joker that likes her rum.</p>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size:1.125em\">Aretta Tarravan</span></h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Female half-orc, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> swab, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> unfriendly<br />A bad tempered harlot whose only signs of orc heritage are big orc ears and on larger incisor.</p>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size:1.125em\">Arzag</span></h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Male hobgoblin, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> swab, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> unfriendly<br />A very tall hobgolbin ex-slaver with a bald head.</p>\n<h3>Crimson \"Cog\" Cogward</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Male human, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> swab, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> unfriendly<br />Crimson Cogward (so called after the color his neck turns when he’s angry) is a loner, and prone to incredible rages and dark moods. Cog gets pleasure from little other than combat and is quick to get into fistfights, whether because of a chance remark or simple bad luck. Cog actually volunteered to join the crew of the <em>Storm Reaver</em>. He has spent his first few days aboard stealing and secreting away goods for barter. Cog loves dark tales. A character that can succeed on telling a dark tale to Cog will gain a +1 bonus on checks to influence Cog. Characters who are fighters and favor muscle over talk, interspursing their talk with grisly details will gain a +1 bonus to influence Cog. However, a failed check is likely to elicit a violent response from the angry sailor.</p>\n<h3>Sador Chumlett</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Male orc, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> swab, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> unfriendly<br />A fat, pushy bully with a shaved head.</p>\n<h3>Jaundiced Sudak</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Female dwarf, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> swab, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> hostile<br />A humorless, greedy mute.</p>\n<h3>Jakes Magpie</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Male dwarf, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> swab, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> hostile<br />A thief caught stealing from the quartermaster's store and sentenced to keelhauling on the character's first day.</p>\n<h2>Riggers</h2>\n<h3>Barefoot Shamms</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Female dwarf, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> rigger, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> neutral<br />A former fisherwoman from Port Krez who never wears shoes.</p>\n<h3>Conchobhar Turlach Tomraan</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Male gnome, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> rigger, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> uncooperative<br />Conchobhar Tomraan is a handsome, honey-tongued gnome who wears a foppish purple hat, an eye patch, and a white silk shirt, and carries a dandyish cane. His appearance is that of someone pretending to be a pirate, rather than a true buccaneer. Conchobhar is a professional gambler who made the mistake of drinking with the <em>Storm Reaver’s</em> crew one night. He has been on ship less than 24 hours at the start of the adventure. Conchobhar is resigned to his fate but is determined to make the most of it, as he’s always yearned for the sea anyway. One thing dominates Conchobhar’s thinking—himself. Conchobhar is also a serial womanizer, and female characters gain a +1 bonus on all checks to influence him. He finds Rosie Cusswell magnificent.</p>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size:1.125em\">\"Ratline\" Rattsberger</span></h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Male dwarf, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> rigger, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> uncooperative<br />A rat-faced dwarf with slightly longer arms and three missing fingers.</p>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size:1.125em\">Maheem</span></h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Male human, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> rigger, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> hostile<br />A big man with a permanent scowl.</p>\n<h3>Slippery Syl</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Male dwarf, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> rigger, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> hostile<br />An unhinged murderer who fled to sea to escape the gallows.</p>\n<h3>Tam \"Narwhal\" Tate</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span> Male dwarf, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span> rigger, <span style=\"color:#ba372a\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> hostile<br />An old friend of Master Scourge with a large ugly nose and half an ear.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":4},"cf":{"id":"temp_wu5utkhw5ta","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Crew of the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
